>Breaks): Filter Freq vs. Felipe Avelar (Kontrast, Zapatistas, Wild 94.9), 
>Kid Loose & Rossi (Br Prod., Kcrh 89.9fm), Aaron Jae (Evil Breaks), Doza 
>(Zapatistas), Carlos Alfonzo & Soulstress (Zapatistas, Audio Metamorphosis, 
>Cal-Trance) Riff Raff (Zapatistas), Michael Allen (Cal-Trance), Andy P 
>(Nocturnalism); Stim-U-Lights will once again fullfill your production 
>expectations and will rock your world with visual pleasure!!! Lite Brite 
>will be providing over 100,000 watts of orgasmic bass that is sure to make 
>you bust one!!! Cal-Trance encourages you to dress in your sexiest outfit 
>as we celebrate our two year anniversary!!! Don't miss the exotic 
>Cal-Trance dancers in two full size go-go cages!!! Located at Polo~Rs Blue 
>Cube 34 mason st. San Francisco, CA. 18+ with a full bar for the 21+ BRING 
>YOUR ID! Can bring: cameras, bags, sex toys, good vibes.Can~Rt bring: 
>drugs, alcohol, weapons, bad vibes. $25 door. Infoline 415.267.6955 
>http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2110 San 
>Francisco California, USA
>

>Administrative Notes -------------------------------------------------
>
>THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every week.
>
>To subscribe to the list, send a message to: 
>sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org
>
>To remove your address from the list, send a message to: 
>sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
>
>Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this list: 
>sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org
>
>If you have events to add to the SFRaves calendar, please publish them by 
>Friday @ Noon to be included in the SFR Calendar Weekly Edition Mailing.
>
>SFRaves is a not for profit entity serving the Bay Area & all forms of
>electronic music for 13 years.

>> Friday, August 12, 2005 ** Moxie **
>> 
>> MOXIE. We want to pump you up!
>> 
>> Moxie's the sister party to (and impetus for) the Moxie Musik radio show 
>> Sundays 9-11pm on WAR 93.7fm/westaddradio.com.  Enthusiasm is encouraged 
>> for this gathering of like-minded, hyphee boogie-mongers.  (Not 
>> booger-mongers, thx.)  Genres can be mis-leading, so we made our own: 
>> techlectro, a mish-mash of electrohaus, techno, tech-house, and (the 
>> über-bastard) rocktronica.
>> 
>> Fact is, we play fun music -- like REALLY fun -- and whatever we may be, we 
>> are never being boring. (We dressed up and fought, then thought: make 
>> amends. And we were never holding back or worried that time would come to 
>> an end.)  We ride the cusp of new music while pulling out those ol' gems 
>> and classics that express the kind of funk and synth revelry we so enjoy, 
>> just so we can play for you!
>> 
>> August 12 special DJs are Solar, Baby Ryan, Animal Style & Qzen.  So pull 
>> on your fun boots, and come jam with us!
>> 
>> More music in your pants, Moxie loves you!

>> Saturday, August 20, 2005 ** [KONTROL] presents PHEEK - LIVE + Claude 
>> VonStroke **
>> 
>> <img src="http://www.kontrolsf.com/august/k03back.jpg" width="450" 
>> height="600" border="0">
>> 
>> 
>> Saturday, August 20th is the return of~E
>> 
>> [KONTROL]
>> 
>> minimal techno + avant house every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery
>> 
>> featuring:
>> 
>> PHEEK ~V LIVE PA (Montreal) m-nus . telegraph . contexterrior . archipel
>> 
>> CLAUDE VonSTROKE (San Francisco) dirtybird records . stepfilm
>> 
>> plus resident DJs: Sammy D ( classic . dirtybird . utensil ) Alland Byallo 
>> ( nightlight . epsionlab . mo's ferry ) Craig Kuna ( concept sf . esdjco . 
>> kodo ) Brian Walls ( ac . stylus . econspiracy )
>> 
>> Digital video art by Econspiracy
>> 
>> Rx Gallery / 132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973 9pm-2am / $10 / 21+ Arrive 
>> early as capacity is very limited.
>> 
>> Check out our website for photos, free music downloads, dj sets and more! 
>> http://www.KONTROLsf.com/
>> 
>> 
>> Hailing from North America~Rs Mecca of minimal sounds, Montreal~Rs Pheek 
>> has been blazing a brilliant path into the future of music, and gaining 
>> international acclaim in the process.  Born Jean Patrice ~SJP~T Remillard, 
>> in 1998 this lifelong music fan, early rave enthusiast, and college radio 
>> DJ attended a performance by Richie Hawtin/Plastikman that would forever 
>> change his perspective on music. Inspired by this performance, he adopted 
>> the moniker Pheek, and within a year he was performing his own original 
>> material live and soon released his first 12~T. In the six years that have 
>> followed, JP has been making a steady ascent to the upper echelons of the 
>> minimal/micro scene~Rs most respected and innovative producers and 
>> performers.  His style is rooted in the funky, minimal sounds of German 
>> tech-house, but is tempered with a heady dose of the ethereal and 
>> experimental, resulting in a unique sound all his own.  In 2005, now with 3 
>> European tours, 4 full length albums and numerous acclaimed EPs on labels 
>> such as Telegraph, Clever Music, Tic Tac Toe, Thinner, Epsilonlab, and his 
>> own Archipel under his belt, Pheek~Rs talent is getting the worldwide 
>> recognition it deserves.  This year has been an especially exciting one for 
>> JP.  After getting extensive play by DJs such as Richie Hawtin and Magda, 
>> Pheek was invited to contribute a track to M-nus Records~R first ever 
>> compilation, Minimize to Maximize, and also landed an EP on Jay Haze~Rs 
>> Contexterrior label, alongside such artists as Haze, Ricardo Villalobos, 
>> and Robag Wruhme.  To top things off, he was invited to perform live at 
>> both Montreal~Rs MUTEK Festival, where he played at the Finale, as well as 
>> Detroit~Rs FUSE-IN Festival (formerly the DEMF) where he delivered an 
>> unforgettable set on the Underground Stage.  Needless to say, we at KONTROL 
>> are hugely excited and honored to be hosting Pheek in his first ever San 
>> Francisco performance.  Do not miss this one kids.
>> 
>> Pheek~Rs website http://www.pheek.com/index.php
>> 
>> Pheek~Rs discography http://www.discogs.com/artist/Pheek
>> 
>> Pheek LIVE @ Detroit~Rs FUSE-IN Festival (May 2005) 
>> http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/Pheek-LiveatFuse-In2005.mp3
>> 
>> 
>> Claude VonStroke (better known to we locals as Barclay Crenshaw) is the man 
>> behind San Francisco~Rs hottest new tech-house label, Dirtybird Records. 
>> Raised in the suburbs of Detroit, Barclay eventually moved to Hollywood and 
>> began working on feature films.  Realizing that the visual medium wasn~Rt 
>> his calling, he moved back to downtown Detroit and fell in love with the 
>> beat.  He began producing music and soon found a way to fuse his skills and 
>> experience in video with his passion for electronic music. He moved to San 
>> Francisco and in 2003 released Intellect, a six hour DVD package, 
>> self-directed and produced, which covered the worldwide electronic music 
>> scene and included interviews with the likes of Derrick May, Juan Atkins, 
>> Swayzak, Derrick Carter, Deep Dish, Magda, Kit Clayton and many more.  In 
>> SF Barclay met Justin and Christian Martin and Worthy and together they 
>> started Dirtybird, with Crenshaw at the helm.  The rest, as they say, is 
>> history.  Dirtybird Records is currently shaking tailfeathers worldwide 
>> with a series of successful releases by Justin Martin & Sammy D and Mr. 
>> VonStroke himself. With remix work by John Tejada and Freaks, and Claude~Rs 
>> upcoming remixes for Frankie, Jay Tripwire, and Justin Martin, it~Rs no 
>> mystery why the Dirtybird has taken flight and is ready to soar to 
>> international prominence.  Bring a bar of soap, because when Claude 
>> VonStroke is behind the decks, it~Rs gonna get dirty.
>> 
>> Claude VonStroke~Rs website 
>> http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/claude_vonstroke.html
>> 
>> Claude VonStroke~Rs discography 
>> http://www.discogs.com/artist/Claude%20VonStroke
>> 
>> Claude VonStroke~Rs dirtybird promo mix (March 2005) - ~SIt~Rs Time For The 
>> P~T http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/audio/mixes/ItsTimeForTheP.mp3

>> Wednesday, August 24, 2005 ** Fine Cut Bodies @ Mighty **
>> 
>> you heard that right. The BayArea Breaks Brigade is at it again with their 
>> 2nd party to benefit their float at this years Love Parade.
>> 
>> 
>> 
>> Fine Cut Bodies (Chi Recordings/Ritmic Records/Moving Target) Budapest, 
>> Hungary
>> 
>> As one of the founders of Chi Recordings, Fine Cut Bodies' tastes are broad 
>> and include all styles of electronic music from breaks to house to techno 
>> and experimental. His taste is guided more by his musical insight and not 
>> by any specific genre: he looks for music that is experimental but not 
>> selfish, interesting but not unlistenable. With the label, club night 
>> residencies, radio show and mixed-genre club mixes he is one of the most 
>> important trend-setting DJs in Hungary. Apart from appearances on the Chi 
>> Recordings label, Kevin has done a remix for the popular Hungarian band 
>> Quimby and worked on remixes for the Swiss label, Ritmic Records and the 
>> Dutch label, Moving Target. In the last few years, he has been a key DJ & 
>> promoter and has helped to develop a significant breaks scene in Hungary. 
>> His first 12~S titled "Deep Lack Of Balance" opened 6th on Muzik 
>> Magazine~Rs breaks chart and his remix for the Swiss Ritmic label called 
>> "The Boomspot" reached 4th on Mixmag~Rs breakbeat chart. More recently, 
>> Kevin's his latest release with EK & Spee, "Terminalhead", just reached 4th 
>> on DJMag~Rs breaks & beats chart and his "Trekk Far" single was picked by 
>> Uberzone for the Y4K compilation on Distinctive Records and remixed by 
>> Elite Force. FCB's tracks are continually being supported by top-level DJs 
>> such as Orbital, Plump DJs, John Tejada, Mr.C, Chris Carter, Hybrid, 
>> Laurent Garnier and Adam Freeland. Recently, he was awarded the title of 
>> ~SBest Hungarian Breaks DJ~T from Impulse Creator, Hungary's largest 
>> internet magazine and his skills behind the decks have brought him around 
>> the world from Europe to Australia to the United States. Currently, FCB is 
>> in the studio working on remixes for Tipper and Carbon Community along with 
>> his next EP called Versus which will consist of collaborations with breaks 
>> heavyweights such as Chris Carter, Hybrid and Elite Force. We are glad to 
>> have him back in San Francisco once again, so come out support a good 
>> cause, and have a wicked good time.
>> 
>> 
>> Along with Bayarea dj's:
>>

Subject: [sfraves] Saturday Night Adventure

So it was Dope... somehow or another... I ended up goin out again w/ Ms
Kitty Adrianna & Mr Squirrel Steve Osteen!!!  YAY!!!  I mean..
seriously... last minute plans are the best, yeah!?  So we were on our way
2 this yummy outdoor that was happening somewhere in SF.. & well.. it was
kinda hard 2 figure out the like map point directions, but I knew where we
1st went 2 Westlake/ Daly City, that wasn't it... so finally we figured it
out & ended up where the well.. la la la la lala la la la la la yada yada
yada & waited @ the Map POint.. nothing happened.  There was this Kegger
that was happening in this Apartment cmplex where a guy took a piss off
the balcony & said "When you gotta go, you go where you can!" & well..
like there was mondo like car, van, jeep traffic & people stopping &
going, so we were confuzed...

So we said fuck it & left & headed 2 Rhythm Method... OK.. LoL..
Heeeeeello 2Daaaaaaay, RM was soooooooooooo Dope!!!  I mean.. ok.. yeah..
we been goin' 2 Shadow Lounge now 4 the past 3 weeks like in a row la la
la, but lastnight was Dope!  I mean.. well.. we got there like late &
there was like 2 hours 2 go, but it was worth it!  So DJ/ Producer from UK
-Spor- was the headliner & we got in during like the middle of his set...
OH Fuckin' A man... he was killin' it!!!  I mean.. I dunno what were his
tracks or whatever, but man... ok.. this is just IMO 'cause I'm like still
fucked w/ the sub genres of Jungle.. but yeah... he was totally throwin'
down Liquid & some hard Dubby shit!!!  So Dope!!!

Then the Rhythm Method Residents all like kinda did this mash up like 4
the last set or maybe it was more like B2B set... DOOOOOOOOPE!!!  Lady Ms
B ( I think that's her name) started that set & she went fuckin' crazy
playing siiiiiiick hard tunes & mixin' it w/ like disco-ie kinda jungle
tracks, Bicolos was somewhere in the middle & well... he claims he train
wrecked back, but if his wreck was where I think he messed up.. then he
played it off pretty good then & like totally didn't... ummmmm.. some
other RM Resi threw down... The Doctor closed the set just strait up hard
ass jungle shit... but then he played a last track after well.. when
people kept yelling "1 more song".. & that was I guess a track they
produced?!  It was Dope.. there was this mondo trancey like melody
overtone that went throughout the song.. it was Dope.. but it was a jungle
track!!  Sick!!!

The Vibe there @ RM was well.. usual I guess.. I mean.. it was pumpin like
always, ya know!  Oh my gosh man... there was this lady there wearing a
crossing guard vest & a red cape & was slam dancing & kept bumping in2
peopel on purpose.. it got sooooo fuckin' annoying!  Then there was lke
these 2 hee hee hee girly girls there who were kinda CooL & danced really
smooth, OK... if I say like how Northbay Girls dance 2 Jungle, you'd get
what i meatn, right?  'Cause that's how they dance... Cute.. & then there
was the Drunk Latino who stood like the front of his body touchiung the DJ
table the tables were on close, then he layed his head on the table, like
me & Adrianna & some1 else carried him 2 a chair 2 sit in or like walked
him while holding him.. then he threw up in a trash can!

LoL.. but it was fun overall!!!  I mean.. we totally made lemonade out of
out lemons lastnight & LoL.. it was So Dope!!  There still is a tinge of
guilt 4 not being able 2 make it 2 the outdoor, but yeah... Hello 2day...
so Dope!  Oh oh oh.. so yeah.. I had 1 of my disposable cams w/ me & LoL..
got a pix w/ Spor & we had this mondo fuckin' Groovy conversation about
well.. music, his American Tour, London, oh gosh.. i can't remember what
else.. but man.. he's soooooo fuckin' NICE!!!  YAY!!!

Then I drove 2 Oakland, parked on a sidealk,  & Steve Drove me home!!! 
Thanks Steve!!!  Muchas Gracias Senorita Meow!!  Love U Yaya!  The End!!!

-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] favorite dj mix atm

I've been really diggin this new mix i downloaded a couple of weeks
ago.  Dj Jonay - Old School Tribal House.  Not sure if that's the real
name of the mix, but it's got some ol skool goodness on it.  Old
Bassbin Twins, Old Freaky Chakra, all sorts of goodies.  It flows from
old tribal, into some acid, then into breaks, and then to
house...wonderful mix, sounds like it's from around 1992-ish.

On the Doors tip, I love emule so much, i got the entire doors
discorgraphy, including singles and live sessions, something like
15-20 albums all together.  I read recently that the doors was one of
the most over rated bands, but i think that's bullshit.  Granted I
dont think Jim lived up to his full potential, in order to do that he
would have had to be somewhat sober some of the time.  but for the
brief period they were all rocking, they were definatly something.

-=20
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

I had a great time at Rhythm method. It was my first real jungle event
I've been to. Took me awhile to get used to the speed, but once I got
into it I understood how hardcore it really is and how fucking pumped
up it can make you. I even got a 2x12 promo vinyl from one of the
dj's. That was bad ass.

Good times
Good times

Adrianna and Osby are two very cool people and I'm happy to have two
new friends.

Subject: [sfraves] Blessings To Russel

One of our old, charming, loving friends has moved on.  I got a phone call 
this morning saying that Russell aka "Seattle Russel"  "Russ and Burl" 
"Concord Russ" had been killed in a motorcycle accident.  He had just 
recently popped back into my life within the last year, good times at 
Stompy, Great times on halloween with Jessee and others.  We used to put 
together parties way back in the day, map points at f-8 to give you an 
idea....  Russ was always upbeat, charming and stubborn as hell!  He was 
working in concord as a piercer, doing very well.  I was always wonderring 
when I would get to talk to Russ in our other worlds....
Russ baby, I am sure you can hear me loud and clear now!!!
Blessings and Much love!!!
Your ass will be missed always!
Danny Picard

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Feeding cows weed

--0-1970099002-1124215977=:76597
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

This is great:
 
http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20050816/od_nm/russia_marijuana_dc;_ylt=Ak1Z5BCP1V45ne8.l21g64btiBIF;_ylu=X3oDMTBiMW04NW9mBHNlYwMlJVRPUCUl
 
But when they get the munchies, watch out! 
 

MOSCOW (Reuters) - Russia's long winter will just fly by for a herd of Russian cows which, a newspaper reported on Tuesday, will be fed confiscated marijuana over the cold months. 

Drug workers said they adopted the unusual form of animal husbandry after they were forced to destroy the sunflowers and maize crops that the 40 tonnes of marijuana had been planted among, Novye Izvestia daily reported.

"There is simply no other way out. You see, the fields are planted with feed crops and if we remove it all the cows will have nothing to eat," a Federal Drugs Control Service spokeswoman for the Urals region of Sverdlovsk told the paper.

"I don't know what the milk will be like after this."

Drug use in Russia took off with the decline of the Soviet Union and police have been fighting drug smugglers -- often shipping heroin from Afghanistan -- for years.

Such large hauls are relatively common, although they are normally burned.

1. paranoid jack & robb g - disaster (atomic hooligan mix)

2. trick & kubic - high (crash house brothers mix)

3. diverted - tholid

4. jhz - chips

5. vandal - mad as hell

6. burnz brotherz - machine (twisted mix)

7. xplosiva & luca baldini - polivox (madox mix)

8. danny howells - breathe (chad will remix)

9. dj hal - psychlone (atomic hooligan mix)

10. goldie lox funktronika (christian hoff house or breakz? mix)

11. azzido da bass - strobelightz (disko blitzer mix)

12. overseer - doomsday (hyper mix)

13. unknown - break boot story

"...What? it's almost Burning Man and you can't bear to pull the 
double-barrel from your mouth because you're not going? Well don't trip! 
The resourceful team of attention whores here at BluegrassRave.com have 
channeled their collective depression into this unbelievably fucking handy 
What Where When Guide For If You're NOT Going To Burning Man. We were 
shocked to find that bars are open, stores are operating regular hours, 
and no major transit services will be interrupting their schedules-- even 
though it's during Burning Man! There are even one or two local cultural 
or community events scheduled the week of Aug 29 - Sep 5. Help yourself 
forget that you're not out heat-stroking in a Port-a-John or 
direction-challenged on makeshift dirt roads called "Gestalt" and 
"Cathexes"... come tear it up with the BluegrassRavers at any or all of 
the Burning Man week events listed below. ..."

I went even-numbered years from '94 to '02, but I broke the even- 
numbered thing for '04 by not going. And, now, moving to Slownoma,  
I've been too busy to even think about going to what I like to call  
the alternative culture's world fair, one of the few things that gets  
bigger AND better.

WBHR

At 05:25 PM 8/16/2005, Karina wrote:
>Question(s) du jour: Are you going to Burning Man? If so - how many 
>years, and what drew you to the event? If you are not going to 
>Burning, have you been in the past? Why / Why not are you going?

Nope.  Attended the original free Beach burns here.  When the event 
moved to Black Rock it was "marketed" by word of mouth, much like 
early underground parties.  3 or 4,000 people attended in 1994 and 
the cost was twenty bucks.

Next year BM was marketed on radio, etc, price went up to around a 
$100 and three times as many peeps attended.  That was it for 
me.  Too much money, security, too many people, and paperwork, for 
heavens sake :-)  Lots of things moved in that direction in the 
golden late nineties.

Personal taste.  If you haven't been it's a good experience...go.

Apollo






Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Question du Jour: Are you going to Burning Man?

I think i'm just not destined for Burning Man.  I'd probably end up
dying or something.  I've tried to go a few times.  The first 2 times
i tried to go, i had tickets in my hand (1998 and 1999) and for one
reason or another had to end up selling my tickets to someone else
because i couldnt go.  I missed the 1999 one because i opted to sell
my ticket and move to SF from Oregon.  I had a few addictions that i
needed to drop badly and going to Burning Man probably wasnt the best
idea at that point and moving away from all my addictions and
influences seemed to the the healthier choice for me.  I was supposed
to go this year, but having a baby due right around the same time, it
again seemed the more intelligent choice to not go and stay here for
the birth of my son.  Wouldnt want the guilt of knowing thinking sorry
i missed your birth, cause i was out in the middle of the desert on
enough acid to kill a horse or some shit like that.  Now the ticket
prices are just too insanely high to make it really worth my while
anymore.  Maybe i'm getting old or something, but if i really wanted I
could take a week off work and take a bunch of drugs away from
civilization and probably accomplish the same thing.  Who knows.=20
Maybe i'll try again next year or something.  Sneak in hiding in
someones speakers or something...hehehe.  I doubt it though, i think
the gods have spoken for me on this one and keep me from going just to
save my life.

--=20
Chester Copperpot

"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

> At 05:25 PM 8/16/2005, Karina wrote:
> >Question(s) du jour: Are you going to Burning Man? If so - how many
> >years, and what drew you to the event? If you are not going to
> >Burning, have you been in the past? Why / Why not are you going?
>=20
> Nope.  Attended the original free Beach burns here.  When the event
> moved to Black Rock it was "marketed" by word of mouth, much like
> early underground parties.  3 or 4,000 people attended in 1994 and
> the cost was twenty bucks.
>=20
> Next year BM was marketed on radio, etc, price went up to around a
> $100 and three times as many peeps attended.  That was it for
> me.  Too much money, security, too many people, and paperwork, for
> heavens sake :-)  Lots of things moved in that direction in the
> golden late nineties.
>=20
> Personal taste.  If you haven't been it's a good experience...go.
>=20
> Apollo

> enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,
> sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and
> Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can
> find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and
> economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond
> what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative
> pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squa=
lor."

haven't done it. got the connectors to link my mixer
to my soundcard, and i think I'll record it in
soundforge. I think that's the easiest way to go. :) 

I tried to get Chris Jackson to let me bring it over
to his studio, but scooping the inch of dust off the
platters on his decks to record is more of a nightmare
than I have at home... Do you want me to record *all*
the tracks on it, or just the accapella?
The tracks are mostly flavored with old school
breaks/hardcore.

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

I was digging through some old internet "archives" recently and came 
upon some posts of mine to the futureculture list (pre 1995) at 
Kulturezone.  The old members list with my name on it is still 
floating around the net so I went to the 
URL  (http://www.evolutionzone.com/kulturezone/) and found this, 
among other things.
What a different world it was then.  So much more.....interesting?

Apollo


T. A. Z.





The Temporary Autonomous Zone, Ontological Anarchy, Poetic Terrorism





Hakim Bey

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

that's right baby.....you heard it first....Evil Breaks bringin Atomic 
Hooligan from the UK with Rhythm Method tearin it up on the outside patio.


Atomic Hooligan (Finger Lickin'/Botchit & Scarper/MOB) United Kingdom

The lads have been meddling with everything breakbeat since the early 90s. 
Matt Welch is a classically trained violinist since the age of 4 and holds 
a Masters in Music. The other Hooligan and Turntablist / Dj extraordinaire 
Terry Ryan is a graduate of the School of Audio engineering and has been 
spinning the decks since he discovered body hair. Their partnership which 
began in a club naturally, is inspiring and their brotherhood is reflected 
in their attitude towards music which is a new and refreshing one, they 
simply refuse to follow the path already walked! Evil Breaks is proud to 
have Terry Hooligan here in San Francisco for a show that is sure to be a 
memorable one.

Saturday, August 20, 2005 ** [KONTROL] presents PHEEK - LIVE + Claude 
VonStroke **

<img src="http://www.kontrolsf.com/august/k03back.jpg" width="450" 
height="600" border="0">


Saturday, August 20th is the return of~E

[KONTROL]

minimal techno + avant house every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery

featuring:

PHEEK ~V LIVE PA (Montreal) m-nus . telegraph . contexterrior . archipel

CLAUDE VonSTROKE (San Francisco) dirtybird records . stepfilm

plus resident DJs: Sammy D ( classic . dirtybird . utensil ) Alland Byallo 
( nightlight . epsionlab . mo's ferry ) Craig Kuna ( concept sf . esdjco . 
kodo ) Brian Walls ( ac . stylus . econspiracy )

Digital video art by Econspiracy

Rx Gallery / 132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973 9pm-2am / $10 / 21+ 
Arrive early as capacity is very limited.

Check out our website for photos, free music downloads, dj sets and more! 
http://www.KONTROLsf.com/


Hailing from North America~Rs Mecca of minimal sounds, Montreal~Rs Pheek 
has been blazing a brilliant path into the future of music, and gaining 
international acclaim in the process.  Born Jean Patrice ~SJP~T Remillard, 
in 1998 this lifelong music fan, early rave enthusiast, and college radio 
DJ attended a performance by Richie Hawtin/Plastikman that would forever 
change his perspective on music. Inspired by this performance, he adopted 
the moniker Pheek, and within a year he was performing his own original 
material live and soon released his first 12~T. In the six years that have 
followed, JP has been making a steady ascent to the upper echelons of the 
minimal/micro scene~Rs most respected and innovative producers and 
performers.  His style is rooted in the funky, minimal sounds of German 
tech-house, but is tempered with a heady dose of the ethereal and 
experimental, resulting in a unique sound all his own.  In 2005, now with 
3 European tours, 4 full length albums and numerous acclaimed EPs on 
labels such as Telegraph, Clever Music, Tic Tac Toe, Thinner, Epsilonlab, 
and his own Archipel under his belt, Pheek~Rs talent is getting the 
worldwide recognition it deserves.  This year has been an especially 
exciting one for JP.  After getting extensive play by DJs such as Richie 
Hawtin and Magda, Pheek was invited to contribute a track to M-nus 
Records~R first ever compilation, Minimize to Maximize, and also landed an 
EP on Jay Haze~Rs Contexterrior label, alongside such artists as Haze, 
Ricardo Villalobos, and Robag Wruhme.  To top things off, he was invited 
to perform live at both Montreal~Rs MUTEK Festival, where he played at the 
Finale, as well as Detroit~Rs FUSE-IN Festival (formerly the DEMF) where 
he delivered an unforgettable set on the Underground Stage.  Needless to 
say, we at KONTROL are hugely excited and honored to be hosting Pheek in 
his first ever San Francisco performance.  Do not miss this one kids.

Pheek~Rs website http://www.pheek.com/index.php

Pheek~Rs discography http://www.discogs.com/artist/Pheek

Pheek LIVE @ Detroit~Rs FUSE-IN Festival (May 2005) 
http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/Pheek-LiveatFuse-In2005.mp3


Claude VonStroke (better known to we locals as Barclay Crenshaw) is the 
man behind San Francisco~Rs hottest new tech-house label, Dirtybird 
Records.  Raised in the suburbs of Detroit, Barclay eventually moved to 
Hollywood and began working on feature films.  Realizing that the visual 
medium wasn~Rt his calling, he moved back to downtown Detroit and fell in 
love with the beat.  He began producing music and soon found a way to fuse 
his skills and experience in video with his passion for electronic music. 
He moved to San Francisco and in 2003 released Intellect, a six hour DVD 
package, self-directed and produced, which covered the worldwide 
electronic music scene and included interviews with the likes of Derrick 
May, Juan Atkins, Swayzak, Derrick Carter, Deep Dish, Magda, Kit Clayton 
and many more.  In SF Barclay met Justin and Christian Martin and Worthy 
and together they started Dirtybird, with Crenshaw at the helm.  The rest, 
as they say, is history.  Dirtybird Records is currently shaking 
tailfeathers worldwide with a series of successful releases by Justin 
Martin & Sammy D and Mr. VonStroke himself. With remix work by John Tejada 
and Freaks, and Claude~Rs upcoming remixes for Frankie, Jay Tripwire, and 
Justin Martin, it~Rs no mystery why the Dirtybird has taken flight and is 
ready to soar to international prominence.  Bring a bar of soap, because 
when Claude VonStroke is behind the decks, it~Rs gonna get dirty.

Claude VonStroke~Rs website 
http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/claude_vonstroke.html

Claude VonStroke~Rs discography 
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Claude%20VonStroke

Claude VonStroke~Rs dirtybird promo mix (March 2005) - ~SIt~Rs Time For 
The P~T http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/audio/mixes/ItsTimeForTheP.mp3

enthusiastic about everybody. "As the bar's customers invariably arrived 
later than we did, and left before us, there was always part of the

Wednesday, August 24, 2005 ** Fine Cut Bodies @ Mighty **

you heard that right. The BayArea Breaks Brigade is at it again with their 
2nd party to benefit their float at this years Love Parade.



Fine Cut Bodies (Chi Recordings/Ritmic Records/Moving Target) Budapest, 
Hungary

As one of the founders of Chi Recordings, Fine Cut Bodies' tastes are 
broad and include all styles of electronic music from breaks to house to 
techno and experimental. His taste is guided more by his musical insight 
and not by any specific genre: he looks for music that is experimental but 
not selfish, interesting but not unlistenable. With the label, club night 
residencies, radio show and mixed-genre club mixes he is one of the most 
important trend-setting DJs in Hungary. Apart from appearances on the Chi 
Recordings label, Kevin has done a remix for the popular Hungarian band 
Quimby and worked on remixes for the Swiss label, Ritmic Records and the 
Dutch label, Moving Target. In the last few years, he has been a key DJ & 
promoter and has helped to develop a significant breaks scene in Hungary. 
His first 12~S titled "Deep Lack Of Balance" opened 6th on Muzik 
Magazine~Rs breaks chart and his remix for the Swiss Ritmic label called 
"The Boomspot" reached 4th on Mixmag~Rs breakbeat chart. More recently, 
Kevin's his latest release with EK & Spee, "Terminalhead", just reached 
4th on DJMag~Rs breaks & beats chart and his "Trekk Far" single was picked 
by Uberzone for the Y4K compilation on Distinctive Records and remixed by 
Elite Force. FCB's tracks are continually being supported by top-level DJs 
such as Orbital, Plump DJs, John Tejada, Mr.C, Chris Carter, Hybrid, 
Laurent Garnier and Adam Freeland. Recently, he was awarded the title of 
~SBest Hungarian Breaks DJ~T from Impulse Creator, Hungary's largest 
internet magazine and his skills behind the decks have brought him around 
the world from Europe to Australia to the United States. Currently, FCB is 
in the studio working on remixes for Tipper and Carbon Community along 
with his next EP called Versus which will consist of collaborations with 
breaks heavyweights such as Chris Carter, Hybrid and Elite Force. We are 
glad to have him back in San Francisco once again, so come out support a 
good cause, and have a wicked good time.


Along with Bayarea dj's:

Greg J (KidBippy.com/Funky Cactus/Lotek) Aaron Jae (Evil 
Breaks/SFBreaks.org/AaronJae.com) Samira (Sister SF) Mancub (Space 
Cowboys) Hypnotech (Addictech) Jay Vigor (StrategiK) Jason Who -

continue on till 2:30 am.

Friday, September 23, 2005 ** September 24 (Saturday) - Loveparade San 
Francisco **

Join us for 3 full days and nights of music, dancing and love in beautiful 
San Francisco. SPECIAL ANNOUNCEMENT: Loveparade San Francisco 2005 FLOATS! 
Featuring Paul Van Dyk, Crystal Method, Ferry Corsten, Carl Cox, Bad Boy 
Bill, Blank & Jones, DJ Dan, Kyau vs. Albert, DJ Icey, St. John, Markus 
Schulz, Mark Farina, Jerry Bonham, Miguel Migs, Above & Beyond, Mike 
Koglin, Dyloot & Tom SIlk, Gianni & Taj, 8ball, Aaron, Jae, Baby Anne, 
BAM, Brad Robinson, Carbon Community, Chris Lobsinger, Derek Hena, Deron, 
DJ Fluid, DJ Hyper, DJ Lowtek, DJ Mes, DJ Seven, DJ Sol, DJ Tracy Bleeke, 
Edgar V, Eric_Hz, Fred Everything, Future Funk Squad, Greg J, Greg Louis, 
HI-8, Hoj, Influence, IZ, J Boogie, J-Break, James Laurer, Jason Who, Jay 
Prasad, Jay Vigor, John Curley, Jondi & Spesh, JT Donaldson, Justin Long, 
Kai and Raji, Kapt'n Kirk, Krystal Jones, KT, Late Night Sneaky, Lee 
Burridge, Lee Coombs, Leedia, Liam Shy, Mancub, Marc O, Max Graham, Mazi, 
Melyss, Mike Frugaletti, Mix Master Amoeaba, M.O.D, Ripple, rrrus, Ryel K, 
Saeed Younan, Samer, Scott Carrelli, Sinikus, Smoove, Soulclap, Sweet P, 
Syd Gris, Tasho, Tanuki, The Geometrist, The Land Shark, Timothy Heit~E. 
More DJ's to be announced. Loveweekend festivities begin Friday, September 
23rd and run through Sunday, September 25th, with the main event - the 
Loveparade - on Saturday, September 24th. We are gearing up for the 2005 
Loveparade in San Francisco on Saturday September 24th. This years parade 
will start at Market & 2nd Street and head west on Market Street to the 
festival location at Civic Center. The parade is schedule to start at 1pm 
and parade to the festival location where the floats will park and all the 
participants can enjoy the multiple genres of music that will be played. 
We are asking for a $5 donation upon entering the festival location, this 
will go to supporting our community partners and other national non-profit 
organizations.

http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2209


Saturday, October 1, 2005 ** Cal Trance 3: Menage A Trois by Cal-Trance 
Recordings **

October 01 (Saturday) ~V

8 hours of non-stop Trance/Nrg/House And Breaks!!  Area 1: Sex On Decks 
(Trance, Nrg, Uk Hard House): Lee Haslam (Tidy, Most Wanted Global-Uk), 
Dyloot (Skills), Tom Slik & Brett James (Skills, Cal-Trance), Enemy 
(Skills), Paul The Fanman & Plate Tektoniks (Audio Metamorphosis, 
Cal-Trance), Majere & Sal Dj (Elektrosorcery,Cal -Trance), Intensify & 
On-It (Cal-Trance, Audio Metamorphosis); Area 2:Gang Banging Beats (House, 
Breaks): Filter Freq vs. Felipe Avelar (Kontrast, Zapatistas, Wild 94.9), 
Kid Loose & Rossi (Br Prod., Kcrh 89.9fm), Aaron Jae (Evil Breaks), Doza 
(Zapatistas), Carlos Alfonzo & Soulstress (Zapatistas, Audio 
Metamorphosis, Cal-Trance) Riff Raff (Zapatistas), Michael Allen 
(Cal-Trance), Andy P (Nocturnalism); Stim-U-Lights will once again 
fullfill your production expectations and will rock your world with visual 
pleasure!!! Lite Brite will be providing over 100,000 watts of orgasmic 
bass that is sure to make you bust one!!! Cal-Trance encourages you to 
dress in your sexiest outfit as we celebrate our two year anniversary!!! 
Don't miss the exotic Cal-Trance dancers in two full size go-go cages!!! 
Located at Polo~Rs Blue Cube 34 mason st. San Francisco, CA. 18+ with a 
full bar for the 21+ BRING YOUR ID! Can bring: cameras, bags, sex toys, 
good vibes.Can~Rt bring: drugs, alcohol, weapons, bad vibes. $25 door. 
Infoline 415.267.6955 
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2110 
San Francisco California, USA


-------------------------------------------------
Administrative Notes 
-------------------------------------------------

THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every week.

To subscribe to the list, send a message to: 
sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a message to: 
sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this list: 
sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

If you have events to add to the SFRaves calendar, please publish them by 
Friday @ Noon to be included in the SFR Calendar Weekly Edition Mailing.

SFRaves is a not for profit entity serving the Bay Area & all forms of 
electronic music for 13 years.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Dancing to a global beat


Marty Lipp

August 21, 2005

Can a microchip process the divine? Can the World Wide Web lead to an 
alternative reality?

A small, growing group of musicians, DJs and fans say yes, using 
gleaming technology to unearth hoary, spiritually imbued music, and 
in the process blending cultures as if to prove that - at least on 
the dance floor - we can all get along.

This subpopulation of international electronica is the focus of 
"Global Beat Fusion" (iUniverse), a new book by Derek Beres, a music 
journalist, yoga instructor and DJ. Beres takes a Joseph 
Campbell-like comparative look at various cultures, then discusses 
the below-the-radar patchwork of musicians who are using this 
oft-sacred music for dance-floor kinetics. He then explains why that 
combination is not as incongruous as it might seem at first glance.

The book postulates that this new genre has spiritual underpinnings 
that can be traced back, in part, to India. Beres follows the 
bifurcated musical evolution that slowly rolled along with the Roma, 
or Gypsies, from northern India to both southern Spain and eastern Europe.

The Internet, the book says, has sped up the usual kind of musical 
transformation that happens when cultures cohabitate, while also 
creating innumerable paths for cross-polination. "It's the same 
process [as the past]," Beres said, "just a new way of doing it."

So you have Spain's Ojos de Brujo combining rap and flamenco; the 
Warsaw Village Band infusing Polish folk music with speed-metal 
ferocity; and Karsh Kale matching traditional Indian instruments with 
electronic ones. With improved connectivity, DJs and audiences can 
hop around the world as easily as dropping quarters in a juke box.

Though optimistic that this exotic electronica will eddy into the 
mainstream one way or another, Beres acknowledges that it is just 
beginning. "I'm covering a scene that hasn't happened yet," he said.

A student of world religions, Beres makes connections between 
contemporary clubs and traditional cultures where ecstatic dancers 
might go into a trance, a cathartic state of release from their 
quotidian cares. During monthly gigs at the Manhattan clubs Nublu and 
SOBs, Beres and the three-member Globesonic DJ crew hold their own 
version of Sunday morning services, spinning bass-booming tunes until 4 a.m.

"The sacred and profane are two sides of the same coin," said Cheb i 
Sabbah, a DJ and creator of a series of international electronica albums.

Sabbah is Algerian-born, but he is from a Jewish Berber family and 
moved to Paris as a child, eventually becoming a DJ there. He now 
lives in San Francisco and has made the transition to music creator, 
though he neither plays an instrument nor sings.

For his latest, "El Kahena" (Six Degrees), Sabbah wanted to "connect 
the dots" of the feminine glimmerings of various North African 
cultures. He went to Morocco and recorded rough-hewn North African 
folk groups in less than state-of-the-art studios. Sabbah likened 
what came next to a sculptor finding the figure inside a slab of 
marble. He overdubbed their "kitchen-made" tracks with electronic 
instrumentation and then remixed the mix to make it dance floor-ready 
and enjoyable to other listeners.

While Sabbah said his music is not solely about healing, he said 
there is an element of that in the music in which he is interested. 
"If someone is smashed out of his head and listening to something 
spiritual, I don't know, maybe they feel more spiritual for that five 
minutes.... If you hear something spiritual, it might awake something 
in you.... Just the vibe of something sacred is important.

"We do need these kinds of places to heal," he said. "In some 
cultures, music has a big place in healing."

Beres said that whether he plays contemplative music for a yoga class 
or chest-thumping, trance-inducing dance music at a club, it is among 
the very few ways for people to become exposed to this kind of music.

"People who want to go deeper will," he said. "If they're having fun, 
mission accomplished."

Marty Lipp can be reached at Martylipp@hotmail.com



http://www.nynewsday.com/entertainment/music/ny-ffcol4387934aug21,0,890085.story?coll=nyc-manheadlines-music

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  KING OF GONZO BLASTS OFF TONIGHT

--=====================_5491453==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

King of gonzo blasts off one last time

Friends gather to see Hunter S Thompson's ashes fired into sky

Dan Glaister in Los Angeles
Saturday August 20, 2005
<http://www.guardian.co.uk>The Guardian

He lived by the gun and he died by the gun. Now the late writer 
Hunter S Thompson, who shot himself in February, is to be blasted 
from a cannon from the back garden of his home in the hills of Aspen, Colorado.

Thompson's ashes have been packed into firework casings and will be 
dispersed today from 34 different shells fired from a gun barrel 
mounted on top of a 150-foot high monument.

The monument, in the form of a clenched fist made symmetrical by the 
addition of a second thumb, is modelled on Thompson's gonzo logo.

"We have never had a request such as this one in our company's 
history," Marcy Zambelli of Zambelli Fireworks told the Pittsburgh 
Post-Gazette. "But we respect the request of the family and have 
actually custom engineered an aerial shell specifically designed to 
carry out his final wish."

A close friend of Thompson's, Michael Cleverly, said: "They've taken 
him out and had him pulverised into a consistency that is optimum for 
the blast, and it'll go straight up. It'll just be taken by the wind 
and drift around Woody Creek, a place that he loved."

Thompson's widow, 32-year-old Anita Thompson, told the Associated 
Press that there would be "no crying, no tears, only celebration" at 
the event, which has been dubbed Hunterpalooza.

"He wanted people to celebrate," she said. "He envisioned it to be a 
beautiful party. The most amazing people would be there. His friends 
would celebrate his life. And he was even specific that there would 
be clinking of ice and whisky."

Thompson, 67, killed himself six months ago with a shot to the head 
with a pistol. His body was found in a chair by his kitchen table, on 
which a typewriter had been placed and a page of writing paper had 
been lined up with the word "counselor" (sic) typed at its centre.

It was a typically enigmatic final word from the inventor of gonzo 
journalism, the stream-of-consciousness style of writing that was a 
chief ingredient in the new journalism of the 1960s and 70s.

The age of gonzo officially began with Thompson's account of a 
drug-fuelled visit to Las Vegas, published in two issues of Rolling 
Stone, and then released, to great acclaim, as Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas.

Much of today's ceremony and the Gonzo monument has been financed by 
the actor Johnny Depp, a friend of Thompson's who portrayed the 
writer in the film version of Fear and Loathing.

The actor, it seems, has drawn an idea from his most recent role as 
Willy Wonka, the chocolate magnate in Charlie and the Chocolate 
Factory for today's ceremony.

In the story, six children who find a ticket inside the wrapper of a 
Wonka chocolate bar are invited to visit his factory. For the funeral 
the procedure is remarkably similar.

Brian Harvey of Boise, Idaho, found a secret ticket hidden inside the 
label on a bottle of the Flying Dog Brewery's Gonzo Imperial Porter.

The ticket grants Mr Harvey and a friend entry to the party, as well 
as transport and accommodation, according to the company's website.

Gonzo Imperial Porter, with a label designed by another close friend 
of Thompson's, British artist Ralph Steadman, has a hefty price tag 
and a worthy cause. Bottles of the beer sell for $95 (£53). Only 
1,500 numbered bottles have been made, and proceeds from the sale go 
to raise money for the Gonzo Memorial Fund. The fund, says the 
company's website, was "set up initially to raise funds for a 
permanent memorial to Hunter so future generations can ponder the 
life of one of the world's great mavericks".

But all is not sweetness and light in Woody Creek, the hamlet 
Thompson made his home. Some residents are emulating the writer's 
curmudgeonly ways.

Jimmy Ibbotson, another close friend of Thompson's and a musician 
with one of the acts performing at tomorrow's ceremony, the Nitty 
Gritty Dirt Band, fired a shotgun at a photographer hoping to take a 
picture of the cannon from his land.

"He was in no danger," Ibbotson told the Aspen Times. "But he won't 
come back, you can be sure of that. I wasn't aiming at him, I just 
wanted to scare his ass. I don't want him coming back here during the 
event. If you want to print the fact that neighbours are shooting at 
paparazzi, please do. It might save us a little hassle on the day of 
the event."

Asked if police had been in touch with him about the incident Mr 
Ibbotson said they had not. "But I don't answer the phone very much," he added.

After the ceremony, Anita Thompson will attend to her role as 
protector of her late husband's legacy.

"I'll be working for Hunter the rest of my life," she said. "I know 
that. I made that commitment, and I'm honoured that I can."

Publication is planned of a third volume of the writer's letters, a 
collection of short stories and an unfinished novel, Polo is My Life. 
Anita Thompson also plans "a small book of wisdom" based on the late 
writer's utterances.

"'Never think you're the smartest one in the room. And never think 
you're the dumbest one in the room.' Little things like that," she said.

http://www.guardian.co.uk/usa/story/0,12271,1552810,00.html

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Party People:

This Sunday, August 21st, it's time to Bang The Drum!  Join us at 
Casino Meadow, outdoors in San Francisco's Golden Gate Park as we 
celebrate 21 years of Hip-Hop Radio!!!!  From 1PM -5PM, 21 MCs and 21 
DJs will bless the stage, together with a B-Boy/B-Girl showcase, Graf 
exhibition, and Beatbox wizardry. This event is Free and open to all 
ages. . .so bring your family, folks, and peoples.  For directions to 
Casino Meadow, check the <http://kevvykev.com/btd.html>map here.  See 
you there!!!




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

> Hailing from North America's Mecca of minimal sounds, Montreal's=20
> *Pheek* has
> been blazing a brilliant path into the future of music, and gaining
> international acclaim in the process. Born Jean Patrice "JP"=20
> Remillard, in
> 1998 this lifelong music fan, early rave enthusiast, and college radio=20=

> DJ
> attended a performance by Richie Hawtin/Plastikman that would forever=20=

> change
> his perspective on music. Inspired by this performance, he adopted the
> moniker Pheek, and within a year he was performing his own original=20
> material
> live and soon released his first 12". In the six years that have=20
> followed,
> JP has been making a steady ascent to the upper echelons of the
> minimal/micro scene's most respected and innovative producers and
> performers. His style is rooted in the funky, minimal sounds of German
> tech-house, but is tempered with a heady dose of the ethereal and
> experimental, resulting in a unique sound all his own. In 2005, now=20
> with 3
> European tours, 4 full length albums and numerous acclaimed EPs on=20
> labels
> such as *Telegraph*, *Clever Music*, *Tic Tac Toe*, *Thinner*,=20
> *Epsilonlab*,
> and his own *Archipel *under his belt, Pheek's talent is getting the
> worldwide recognition it deserves. This year has been an especially=20
> exciting
> one for JP. After getting extensive play by DJs such as Richie Hawtin=20=

> and
> Magda, Pheek was invited to contribute a track to *M-nus Records'*=20
> first
> ever compilation, *Minimize to Maximize*, and also landed an EP on Jay
> Haze's *Contexterrior* label, alongside such artists as Haze, Ricardo
> Villalobos, and Robag Wruhme. To top things off, he was invited to=20
> perform
> live at both Montreal's *MUTEK Festival*, where he played at the=20
> Finale, as
> well as Detroit's *FUSE-IN Festival* (formerly the DEMF) where he=20
> delivered
> an unforgettable set on the Underground Stage. Needless to say, we at
> KONTROL are hugely excited and honored to be hosting Pheek in his=20
> *first
> ever San Francisco performance*. Do not miss this one, kids.

http://www.groundscore.net/board/viewtopic.php?t=13569

Eklektic Turns 8 / Fuck Off And Dance

What began in 1997 as three girls' party-with-heart, San Francisco's
infamous Eklektic, lived up to its name for the five years that it ran as
a weekly. A drum & bass night at the core, Eklektic developed to involve
everything from dub to disco to hip hop to 'ardcore to 2- step to breaks.

With a strong foundation in local talent and tough rank of residents,
Eklektic and its production company, Groundscore, brought top-shelf sounds
to a warm and enthusiastic reception in the "red light district" of their
dancefloor.

There are few headliners who have yet to grace the decks over the years as
the party has lived on as a series of one-offs. Roni Size, however, is one
of them, and September 2 marks Eklektic's 8 Year Anniversary by showcasing
the one who can truly reprazent. Groundscore welcomes the opportunity to
introduce one unmistakable vibe to another. Not to be missed!

Eklektic's 8 Year Anniversary with Roni Size, Gridlok, 4Real, Mal, Audio
Angel, MCs Duh & Colonel, Felix the Dog, Rascue, and Jamin. September 2,
2005 / Doors open at 10pm / 1015 Folsom at 6th St.

Nostalgic photo thread can be found on this site.

Keep Your Ear To The Ground!

At 12:00 AM 8/20/2005, you wrote:
>What a different world it was then.  So much more.....interesting?

I too was influenced by these writings prior to starting to promote and 
throw events; mostly TAZ and Immediatism.. However, I learned a little 
latter that Peter Lamborn Wilson is quite the pedophile apologist as well. 
I haven't verified directly any writings, but unchallenged discussion was 
brought up on an academic/research oriented anarchist email list I've been 
on for a while..  I suppose TAZ standing on its own is ok, but the whole 
package may be a little tainted..

Having gone through a TAZ of sorts.. about 6 months in length and waning 
for a year & a half. It wasn't more interesting then.. Just a wild time 
where anything was possible.... Anything is possible today as well and I 
for one am never looking back on the past as something that should return 
in the exact same way... :)

Best,
--Mike

Ah, pedophiles.  Seems everyone is suspect these days:)

Pedophilia and Star Trek

Ellen LadowskyThu Aug 18, 3:45 PM ET

The LA Times recently ran a story about the Child Exploitation 
Section of the Toronto Sex Crimes Unit, which contained a 
mind-boggling statistic: of the more than 100 offenders the unit has 
arrested over the last four years, "all but one" has been "a 
hard-core Trekkie." Blogger Ernest Miller thought this claim was 
improbable. "I could go to a science fiction convention," he 
explained "and be less likely to find that 99+ percent of the 
attendees were hard-core Trekkies." While there may be quibbling 
about the exact numbers, the Toronto detectives claim that the 
connection is undeniable.

Continued: 
<http://news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&u=/huffpost/20050818/cm_huffpost/005857>http://news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&u=/huffpost/20050818/cm_huffpost/005857

Makes me sorta question my own devotion to Star Trek....

Apollo

<http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

RAVING IS NOT A CRIME

---------- Forwarded message ----------
From: machine dance <a@gmail.com>
Date: Aug 21, 2005 8:27 PM
Subject: [dcraves] evol intent's account of how ravers in utah are treated=
=20
like criminals
To: STFU <dcraves@hyperreal.org>

posted on the buzzboard, pretty fucked up.

http://www.buzzlife.com/forums/showthread.php?t=3D62975

the official statement from the Utah County Sheriff can be found here:
http://www.utahcountyonline.org/New..._System=3DSHERIFF


"Last night, I was booked to play an event about an hour outside of
Salt Lake City, Utah. The hype behind this show was huge, they presold
700 tickets and they expected up to 3,000 people total. The promoters
did an amazing job with the show.. they even made slipmats with the
flyers on them to promote in local shops.

So, we got to the show around 11:15 or so and it was really cool. It
was all outdoors, in a valley surrounded by huge mountains. They had
an amazing light show flashing on to a mountain behind the site, the
sound was booming, the crowd was about 1500 people thick and
everything just seemed too good to be true really. Well...

At about 11:30 or so, I was standing behind the stage talking with
someone when I noticed a helicopter pulling over one of the mountain
tops. I jokingly said "Oh look, here comes big brother" to the person
I was with. I wasn't far off.

The helicopter dipped lower and lower and started shining its lights
on the crowd. I was kind of in awe and just sat and watched this thing
circle us for a minute. As I looked back towards the crowd I saw a guy
dressed in camoflauge walking by, toting an assault rifle. At this
point, everyone was fully aware of what was going on . A few "troops"
rushed the stage and cut the sound off and started yelling that
everyone "get the fuck out of here or go to jail". This is where it
got really sticky.

No one resisted. That's for sure. They had police dogs raiding the
crowd of people and I saw a dog signal out a guy who obviously had
some drugs on him. The soldiers attacked the guy (4 of them on 1), and
kicked him a few times in the ribs and had their knees in his back and
sides. As they were cuffing him, there was about 1000 kids trying to
leave in the backdrop, peacefully. Next thing I know, A can of fucking
TEAR GAS is launched into the crowd. People are running and screaming
at this point. Girls are crying, guys are cussing... bad scene.

Now, this is all I saw with my own eyes, but I heard plenty of other
accounts of the night. Now this isnt gossip I heard from some candy
raver, these are instances cited straight out of the promoters mouth..

- One of the promoters friends (a very small female) was attacked by
one of the police dogs. As she struggled to get away from it, the
police tackled her. 3 grown men proceeded to KICK HER IN THE STOMACH.

- The police confiscated 3 video tapes in total. People were trying to
document what was happening out there. The police saw one guy filming
and ran after him, tackled him and his camera fell, and luckily.. his
friend grabbed it and ran and got away. priceless footage. That's not
all though. Out of 1,500 people, there's sure to be more footage.

- The police were rounding up the staff of the party and the main
promoter went up to them with the permit for the show and said "here,
I have the permit." The police then said, "no you don't" and ripped
the permit out of his hand. Then, they put an assault rifle to his
forehead and said "get the fuck out of here right now."



Now.. let's get the facts straight here.

This event was 100% legal. They had every permit the city told them
they needed. They had a 2 MILLION DOLLAR insurance policy for the
event. They had liscenced security guards at the gates confiscating
any alcohol or drugs found upon entry (yes, they searched every car on
the way in). Oh, I suppose I should mention that they arrested all the
security guards for possession.

Oh another interesting fact.. the police did not have a warrant. The
owner of the land already has a lawsuit against the city for something
similar. A few months ago, she rented her land for a party and the
police raided that as well. And catch this, the police forced her to
LEAVE HER OWN PERSONAL PROPERTY. That's right. They didnt arrest her,
but made her leave her own property!!!

Don't get it twisted, this is all going down in probably THE most
conservative state in the USA. And this is scary.. a gross violation
of our civil liberties. The police wanted this party shut down, so
they made it happen. Even though everything about this event was
legal. The promoters spent over $ 20,000 on this show and did
everything they had to to make it legit, only to have it taken away
from them by a group of radical neo-con's with an agenda.

This was one of the scariest things I have ever witnessed in person. I
can't even begin to describe how surreal it was. Helicopters, assault
rifles, tear gas, camoflauge-wearing soldiers.... why? Was that really
necessary?

This needs to be big news across the USofA. At least in our music
scene (edm as a whole)... this could happen to any of us at any time.
When we're losing the right to gather peacefully, we're also letting
the police set a standard of what we can get away with. And I think
that's BULLSHIT!

The system fucked up last night... They broke up a party that was 100%
legal and they physically hurt a lot of people there at the same time.
The promoters already have 6 lawsuits ready to file with their lawyers
and the ACLU is already involved.

I'm sure some pictures (and hopefully some video) will surface soon.
I'll make sure to post them up here on 404, so you can see the Police
State of America at work.

p.s. - there are more stories of police brutality that i'll post up
later. gotta hit the airport soon. can't wait to get the fuck out of
this shit hole state"

Dr. Robert Moog passed away today.

ASHEVILLE, N.C. ­ August 21, 2005 ­ Bob died this afternoon at his home in
Asheville, N.C. He was 71. Bob was diagnosed with brain cancer (glioblastoma
multiforme or GBM) in late April 2005. He had received both radiation
treatment and chemotherapy to help combat the disease. He is survived by his
wife, Ileana, his five children, Laura Moog Lanier, Matthew Moog, Michelle
Moog-Koussa, Renee Moog, and Miranda Richmond; and the mother of his children,
Shirleigh Moog.

Bob was warm and outgoing. He enjoyed meeting people from all over the world.
He especially appreciated what Ileana referred to as "the magical connection"
between music-makers and their instruments.

No public memorial is planned. Fans and friends can direct their sympathies or
remembrances to www.caringbridge.com/visit/bobmoog.





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Please pass this on.  I believe people are starting to organize around

--------------------------------------
UTAH RAVERS TREATED LIKE TERRORISTS! EVOL INTENT'S ACCOUNT OF THE INCIDENT!

Originally Posted by knick evl ntnt

Last night, I was booked to play an event about an hour outside of Salt
Lake City, Utah. The hype behind this show was huge, they presold 700
tickets and they expected up to 3,000 people total. The promoters did an
amazing job with the show.. they even made slipmats with the flyers on
them to promote in local shops.

So, we got to the show around 11:15 or so and it was really cool. It was
all outdoors, in a valley surrounded by huge mountains. They had an
amazing light show flashing on to a mountain behind the site, the sound
was booming, the crowd was about 1500 people thick and everything just
seemed too good to be true really. Well...

At about 11:30 or so, I was standing behind the stage talking with
someone when I noticed a helicopter pulling over one of the mountain
tops. I jokingly said "Oh look, here comes big brother" to the person I
was with. I wasn't far off.

The helicopter dipped lower and lower and started shining its lights on
the crowd. I was kind of in awe and just sat and watched this thing
circle us for a minute. As I looked back towards the crowd I saw a guy
dressed in camoflauge walking by, toting an assault rifle. At this
point, everyone was fully aware of what was going on . A few "troops"
rushed the stage and cut the sound off and started yelling that everyone
"get the fuck out of here or go to jail". This is where it got really
sticky.

No one resisted. That's for sure. They had police dogs raiding the crowd
of people and I saw a dog signal out a guy who obviously had some drugs
on him. The soldiers attacked the guy (4 of them on 1), and kicked him a
few times in the ribs and had their knees in his back and sides. As they
were cuffing him, there was about 1000 kids trying to leave in the
backdrop, peacefully. Next thing I know, A can of fucking TEAR GAS is
launched into the crowd. People are running and screaming at this point.
Girls are crying, guys are cussing... bad scene.

Now, this is all I saw with my own eyes, but I heard plenty of other
accounts of the night. Now this isnt gossip I heard from some candy
raver, these are instances cited straight out of the promoters mouth..

- One of the promoters friends (a very small female) was attacked by one
of the police dogs. As she struggled to get away from it, the police
tackled her. 3 grown men proceeded to KICK HER IN THE STOMACH.

- The police confiscated 3 video tapes in total. People were trying to
document what was happening out there. The police saw one guy filming
and ran after him, tackled him and his camera fell, and luckily.. his
friend grabbed it and ran and got away. priceless footage. That's not
all though. Out of 1,500 people, there's sure to be more footage.

- The police were rounding up the staff of the party and the main
promoter went up to them with the permit for the show and said "here, I
have the permit." The police then said, "no you don't" and ripped the
permit out of his hand. Then, they put an assault rifle to his forehead
and said "get the fuck out of here right now."



Now.. let's get the facts straight here.

This event was 100% legal. They had every permit the city told them they
needed. They had a 2 MILLION DOLLAR insurance policy for the event. They
had liscenced security guards at the gates confiscating any alcohol or
drugs found upon entry (yes, they searched every car on the way in). Oh,
I suppose I should mention that they arrested all the security guards
for possession.

Oh another interesting fact.. the police did not have a warrant. The
owner of the land already has a lawsuit against the city for something
similar. A few months ago, she rented her land for a party and the
police raided that as well. And catch this, the police forced her to
LEAVE HER OWN PERSONAL PROPERTY. That's right. They didnt arrest her,
but made her leave her own property!!!

Don't get it twisted, this is all going down in probably THE most
conservative state in the USA. And this is scary.. a gross violation of
our civil liberties. The police wanted this party shut down, so they
made it happen. Even though everything about this event was legal. The
promoters spent over $ 20,000 on this show and did everything they had
to to make it legit, only to have it taken away from them by a group of
radical neo-con's with an agenda.

This was one of the scariest things I have ever witnessed in person. I
can't even begin to describe how surreal it was. Helicopters, assault
rifles, tear gas, camoflauge-wearing soldiers.... why? Was that really
necessary?

This needs to be big news across the USofA. At least in our music scene
(edm as a whole)... this could happen to any of us at any time. When
we're losing the right to gather peacefully, we're also letting the
police set a standard of what we can get away with. And I think that's
BULLSHIT!

The system fucked up last night... They broke up a party that was 100%
legal and they physically hurt a lot of people there at the same time.
The promoters already have 6 lawsuits ready to file with their lawyers
and the ACLU is already involved.

I'm sure some pictures (and hopefully some video) will surface soon.
I'll make sure to post them up here on 404, so you can see the Police
State of America at work.

p.s. - there are more stories of police brutality that i'll post up
later. gotta hit the airport soon. can't wait to get the fuck out of
this shit hole state.

www.buzzlife.com/forums/showthread.php
<http://www.buzzlife.com/forums/showthread.php?t=3D62975>

Subject: [sfraves] utah rave raided - tear gas, assault rifles, dogs...

Please pass this on.  I believe people are starting to
organize around
this incident.

UTAH RAVERS TREATED LIKE TERRORISTS! EVOL INTENT'S
ACCOUNT OF THE 
INCIDENT!

Originally Posted by knick evl ntnt

Last night, I was booked to play an event about an
hour outside of Salt
Lake City, Utah. The hype behind this show was huge,
they presold 700
tickets and they expected up to 3,000 people total.
The promoters did 
an
amazing job with the show.. they even made slipmats
with the flyers on
them to promote in local shops.

So, we got to the show around 11:15 or so and it was
really cool. It 
was
all outdoors, in a valley surrounded by huge
mountains. They had an
amazing light show flashing on to a mountain behind
the site, the sound
was booming, the crowd was about 1500 people thick and
everything just
seemed too good to be true really. Well...

At about 11:30 or so, I was standing behind the stage
talking with
someone when I noticed a helicopter pulling over one
of the mountain
tops. I jokingly said "Oh look, here comes big
brother" to the person I
was with. I wasn't far off.

The helicopter dipped lower and lower and started
shining its lights on
the crowd. I was kind of in awe and just sat and
watched this thing
circle us for a minute. As I looked back towards the
crowd I saw a guy
dressed in camoflauge walking by, toting an assault
rifle. At this
point, everyone was fully aware of what was going on .
A few "troops"
rushed the stage and cut the sound off and started
yelling that 
everyone
"get the fuck out of here or go to jail". This is
where it got really
sticky.

No one resisted. That's for sure. They had police dogs
raiding the 
crowd
of people and I saw a dog signal out a guy who
obviously had some drugs
on him. The soldiers attacked the guy (4 of them on
1), and kicked him 
a
few times in the ribs and had their knees in his back
and sides. As 
they
were cuffing him, there was about 1000 kids trying to
leave in the
backdrop, peacefully. Next thing I know, A can of
fucking TEAR GAS is
launched into the crowd. People are running and
screaming at this 
point.
Girls are crying, guys are cussing... bad scene.

Now, this is all I saw with my own eyes, but I heard
plenty of other
accounts of the night. Now this isnt gossip I heard
from some candy
raver, these are instances cited straight out of the
promoters mouth..

- One of the promoters friends (a very small female)
was attacked by 
one
of the police dogs. As she struggled to get away from
it, the police
tackled her. 3 grown men proceeded to KICK HER IN THE
STOMACH.

- The police confiscated 3 video tapes in total.
People were trying to
document what was happening out there. The police saw
one guy filming
and ran after him, tackled him and his camera fell,
and luckily.. his
friend grabbed it and ran and got away. priceless
footage. That's not
all though. Out of 1,500 people, there's sure to be
more footage.

- The police were rounding up the staff of the party
and the main
promoter went up to them with the permit for the show
and said "here, I
have the permit." The police then said, "no you don't"
and ripped the
permit out of his hand. Then, they put an assault
rifle to his forehead
and said "get the fuck out of here right now."



Now.. let's get the facts straight here.

This event was 100% legal. They had every permit the
city told them 
they
needed. They had a 2 MILLION DOLLAR insurance policy
for the event. 
They
had liscenced security guards at the gates
confiscating any alcohol or
drugs found upon entry (yes, they searched every car
on the way in). 
Oh,
I suppose I should mention that they arrested all the
security guards
for possession.

Oh another interesting fact.. the police did not have
a warrant. The
owner of the land already has a lawsuit against the
city for something
similar. A few months ago, she rented her land for a
party and the
police raided that as well. And catch this, the police
forced her to
LEAVE HER OWN PERSONAL PROPERTY. That's right. They
didnt arrest her,
but made her leave her own property!!!

Don't get it twisted, this is all going down in
probably THE most
conservative state in the USA. And this is scary.. a
gross violation of
our civil liberties. The police wanted this party shut
down, so they
made it happen. Even though everything about this
event was legal. The
promoters spent over $ 20,000 on this show and did
everything they had
to to make it legit, only to have it taken away from
them by a group of
radical neo-con's with an agenda.

This was one of the scariest things I have ever
witnessed in person. I
can't even begin to describe how surreal it was.
Helicopters, assault
rifles, tear gas, camoflauge-wearing soldiers.... why?
Was that really
necessary?

This needs to be big news across the USofA. At least
in our music scene
(edm as a whole)... this could happen to any of us at
any time. When
we're losing the right to gather peacefully, we're
also letting the
police set a standard of what we can get away with.
And I think that's
BULLSHIT!

The system fucked up last night... They broke up a
party that was 100%
legal and they physically hurt a lot of people there
at the same time.
The promoters already have 6 lawsuits ready to file
with their lawyers
and the ACLU is already involved.

I'm sure some pictures (and hopefully some video) will
surface soon.
I'll make sure to post them up here on 404, so you can
see the Police
State of America at work.

p.s. - there are more stories of police brutality that
i'll post up
later. gotta hit the airport soon. can't wait to get
the fuck out of
this shit hole state.

www.buzzlife.com/forums/showthread.php
<http://www.buzzlife.com/forums/showthread.php?t=62975>

http://www.utrave.org/
