(another account with more links, below)

Originally Posted by *Alisha*
Alisha's account

This is my account of events that unfolded while
attending an outdoor
electronic music event. I arrived shortly before 9 pm
sharp. My two
friends and i set up camp and headed to the stage. All
was well and
peaceful enjoying the music to the full extent while
dancing. Around
11:30pm or so i noticed a helicopter flying above the
main stage of the
event. At this point i am confused. The chopper began
to come in closer
to the stage with a search light focused on the crowd.
I got nervous 
and
still very confused and walked over to find my two
friends I had 
arrived
with earlier. Just as soon as i did that I looked over
at my friend and
asked "whats going on". That is when I was greeted by
a man in full 
army
attire, gas mask and all. He said to leave. I said
what whats going on,
at which point i was brutally attacked. Thrown to the
ground and in the
scuffle punched in the face by swat. That was not it
either. I suppose 
i
posed some a threat as another swat member rushed over
to subdue me to
the ground puting his knee in my back and arresting
me. At that point I
am screaming to a patron "whats going on?" He is just
as confused as I
am. At that point another swat member came over and
kicked me in the
leg. Let me tell you that I also only weigh 130
pounds. I had three
grown men attack and beat me and throw me to ground
for absolutely no
reason at all. Not to mention being dragged to a van
and violently 
being
tossed in and taken to jail. Fined for resisting
arrest and another
outrageous charge. I do need to mention also that
while this is all
happening to me at the same time my two friends, a boy
and girl were
trying to reach out and stop them, at that point they
were attacked and
arrested as well.

That is my account. I have all the bruises to show.
Our basic human
rights were violated in a very bad way. We have to
tell our story. Do
all that you can and dont be afraid to speak up.

Read the rest of the official statements, including
bruise pics:

http://www.utrave.org/showthread.php?t=20030

 RAVING IS NOT A CRIME

 INTOXICATION IS NOT A CRIME

and locked up each and every year in this country?

That's no small number, and it's only gonna grow, and this is just a=20
warm-up.=20

I understand that there are some mega-prisons being built in remote areas=
=20
out west that can house a lot more people, and that's a trend that will not=
=20
reverse itself anytime soon.

This really is a war and we're getting our asses kicked all over the block,=
=20
up and down the street, and hard too, and it's not going to stop, and we on=
=20
the side that's getting the shit beat out of it is a) completely=20
disorganized, largely in part to that we buy into their shit about getting=
=20
high as being a 'bad' 'shameful' thing worthy of punishment b) approaching=
=20
the same spot as the Jews/Gypsy's were in the late 1920's early 1930's in=
=20
terms of level of persecution that we are experiencing. c) not doing a=20
damned thing to fight this to get ourselves out of this position, because d=
)=20
we've got a real blind-spot towards seeing that this is truly a fight to th=
e=20
death war partly because it crept up on us kinda slowly.

Scoff at that if you must, but consider this.

A 'dirty' piss test isn't quite a Star of David, yet, but considering the=
=20
negative impact it can have on one, where say, keeping, or getting a job,=
=20
and providing for not only yourself but your family too, is at stake, and=
=20
all of a sudden the hit or two you have at night to unwind has some real=20
negative and possibly grave real-world implications.

Shit a friend of mine in Menlo Park lost his marriage and nearly had his=20
kids taken away and his house because a nieghbor saw his two pot plants tha=
t=20
he was growing indoors through his window and turned him into the cops.

Shit like that happens every day in this country now doesn't it?

About 6-7 years ago I was hanging out with a friend of a friend, while we=
=20
were on an aborted trip to burning man, and he laid the whole 'drug users=
=20
are America's equivalent of the Jews in Germany' trip on me for the first=
=20
time and since he was a bit of a undereducated, drug addled flake, kinda=20
like me, I guess, I was pretty dismissive at first, but given my family=20
background, I found myself thinking about this statement more and more over=
=20
the years and i've seen more compelling evidence towards the truth of this=
=20
than I have towards seeing it as a dumb joke told by somebody that didn't=
=20
know what they were talking about.

One of the corrallaries to this line of thinking that came up was why the=
=20
absolute vociferousness of these attacks on our culture?

I mean, c'mon, helicopters, dogs, SWAT teams in full riot gear, all that to=
=20
break up a peaceful, lawful, party?

That's a bit much, don't you think?

Why all that heat?

Then it hit me.

They're shit scared of us and what we represent because, ultimately, we're =
a=20
threat to them and their game.

See, you just don't go after people like that if you think that they're=20
harmless to you and themselves, why would you?

What these people that have the power in this country want to do is keep=20
their little death machine rolling, and well, if you're constantly going ou=
t=20
to all night dance parties, every second that you do that, you've unplugged=
=20
from their toxic 'make you fat and stupid but not happy'=20
media-food-hospital-criminal-justice-re-hab infrastructure and it makes you=
=20
that much harder to lock up prematurely in one of their hospitals or prison=
s=20
where they will literally and slowly milk your carcass to death.

They hate that and they will go out of their way to destroy anything that=
=20
gets in the way of that.

I'm starting to see this as being really heinous process being that's been=
=20
happening to millions of my fellow Americans, for decades now, for no other=
=20
reason than to satiate these greedy pricks sadistic need and lust for power=
.

Morgan Spurlock's 'Super-Size Me' approach, where he swallows their crap=20
whole hook, line and sinker, really helped me see a lot of this.=20

I sat down and asked myself one day, well if they don't want me playing=20
video games, consorting with whores and otherwise partying like a rock-star=
,=20
what is it that they DO want me to be doing with my life and time?

Then I turned on the TV and there was my answer.

The next question I asked myself was OK, if I do everything that they're=20
telling me to do through that video-box, if I were to do that, what would I=
=20
look like after an extended period of time?

For that, all I had to do is step outside my house and go out in public.

Ugh, nasty, everywhere I go in this country, my fellow americans have reall=
y=20
let themselves go, as of late, and in a really big way too.

If Coke and Pepsi and McDonald's and the rest of the crap they spend=20
millions and millions of dollars advertising each and every day, don't have=
=20
anything to do with that then I really am a retard.

Then, if I go to a rave, it's not so much that there's this huge drop in=20
morbidly obese people that make up the crowd, even though there is, won't=
=20
see a lot of fat people there, but it just seems that everyone's overall=20
health is better than were you to draw that many people out of the non-rave=
r=20
general population.

Might have less to do with doing drugs like a juvenile and more to do with=
=20
the fact that you've been spending upwards of 12 hours in one night getting=
=20
yourself exercised by dancing all night long.

So then this really begs obvious question, which is, given the demonstrable=
=20
health benefits a dancing lifestyle has and the negative effects a tv=20
watching, stupid ugly vehicle driving, fast-food eating life has wouldn't=
=20
the 'powers-that-be' bend over backwards to nurture the positive?

This is where things take a dark turn, if you think about it long=20
enough......

They want it this way.

Dumbed down, so it's a lot, lot, easier to follow Fox News, eating and=20
drinking their swill, which gets you nice and slow and lumbering, and if yo=
u=20
start to feel antsy and have a vague floating sense of anxiety you can take=
=20
their witches brew addictive pills that are legal, xanax, anyone, which=20
hopefully will generate side effects so you can take even more of their=20
legal soul and pain-killing pills, and you'll just get more and more used t=
o=20
generally deteriorating life conditions, they want all this and more becaus=
e=20
that will make us weak, and therefore more malleable as a people so that if=
=20
Janet Jackson shows a little skin on TV they can get us all worked up in=20
nice hot lather, or get us to sign up for a war, any war, doesn't matter,=
=20
once you figure out how to do this like this, you can do it all the time,=
=20
anywhere.

This is so slimey and utterly pervasive that words escape me in describing=
=20
how awful this is.

And they're going to keep it this way and they're going to come at us with=
=20
every tool in their utility belts if they ever see us emerge, and i hate to=
=20
say this but they are going to win these battles, because, well, they're th=
e=20
ones with the guns and helicopters and blanket, coast to coast 24/7 control=
=20
of the media and dogs and and satelittes pepper spray and jails and=20
handcuffs and the courts, while we may outnumber them, we're completely=20
fucking unarmed, we have absolutely none of that sort of ordnance or=20
firepower at our disposal and most of us are blithefully unaware that this=
=20
really is a war on us, and believe it or not, these mother-fuckers play for=
=20
keeps.

it's so bad and so entrenched that i don't even think a revolution of any=
=20
sort will eliminate this evil, getting militant to match these assholes=20
isn't a way i want to go, so i'm kinda at my wits end as what to do, what=

sort of approach to take to help solve this. the only way I see it coming t=
o=20
an end is through some long drawn out organic process that's going to hurt=

millions more people over a long period of time.

be nice if someone could figure a way out of all this, i'd be so down for=

that.

plus it's a larger puzzle than i'm seeing all the pieces of

what I have been doing to take my mind off of all this is to spend more tim=
e=20
working in the garden, odd how that's turned into a place of solace for me=

as things have gotten so much grimmer around me, but that's a whole 'nother=
,=20
lots lots happier thread somewheres soon down the road.

Police Raid Outdoor Music Event
by Parker Pinette Monday August 22, 2005 at 04:30 AM
<mailto:ppinette@gmail.com>ppinette@gmail.com
Numerous accounts from attendees of an outdoor electronic music event 
in Utah county indicate excessive force used by Sherrif and SWAT 
officers. A video has surfaced depicting officers dressed in full 
military fatigues raiding the main stage of the event. Local news 
stations side with police in initial reports.

Attendees of the outdoor electronic music event dubbed "Versus II" 
taking place the evening of Saturday, August 20th in the Diamond Fork 
area of Spanish Fork Canyon in Utah County arrived at the event with 
confidence that the concert organizers had obtained the proper 
permits and legal clearance to hold the event. Personal accounts 
available at the local electronic community 
website<http://utrave.org>utrave<http://utrave.org>.org paint a scene 
of police brutality and mayhem, many accounts bearing eyewitness to 
the forceful arrest of young girls.

Reports state that at approximately 11:30pm upwards of 90 officers, 
many wearing full camouflage gear, gathered from Sherrif and SWAT 
departments in surrounding areas stormed the previously peaceful 
gathering dedicated to music and dance. At least 1 helicopter was 
dispatched, along with large tranport vehicles designated for both 
officers and detainees. Numerous statements from attendees indicate 
excessive force being exerted by many officers. Inuries including 
mild to severe bruises and cuts have been reported by party goers as 
young as age 17.

The Utah County Sherrif's Office has expressed a long term vendetta 
against what they call "Rave" parties. Statements from the Sherrif's 
office as well as eyewitness accounts make it clear that this was a 
premeditated attack on the promoters and community supporting these 
events. While the Sherrif's office has stated that many drugs and 
pieces of paraphernalia were obtained, they fail to note how many of 
the 60+ citations were for drug violations. Many accounts indicate 
the majority of citations and arrests were for resisting arrest. The 
Sherrif's office states that the party was raided on the grounds of 
failure to obtain a mass gathering permit for an event hosting more 
than 250 attendees. Reports vary as to the number in attendance, 
estimation ranging from 250 to 1,400. Controversy exists as to 
whether a mass gathering permit was actually obtained, however, a 
Health Department permit was obtained, and hired security and 
emergency medical service personnel were on site.

Many eyewitness accounts indicate that officers singled out party 
goers attempting to document the events on camcorders, cameras and 
camera phones. Victims have claimed that officers knocked cameras out 
of the hands of the owner, even confiscating some. Luckily, one 
<http://homepage.mac.com/apexgrin/FileSharing2.html>video has 
surfaced, and is quickly spreading across the internet, as well as 
being featured by at least one local news station. The video clearly 
displays a large number of officers dressed in full camouflage 
fatigues, some brandishing rifles. In the higher quality version of 
the video, which includes sound, it is apparent that the use of a 
taser was employed. While the video is somewhat unclear at times, the 
viewer can plainly see an officer atop a young girl fully subdued on 
the ground on her stomach; he swings on her at least twice, as more 
officers rush forward to manhandle the girl. It is clear that many 
others were subdued using similar levels of force.

Initial reports from local news stations side with the Sherrif's 
Office, one anchor calling the event a "drug party" without batting 
an eye. Reports tend to focus on the drugs and paraphernalia acquired 
by police, rather than the obvious violation of civil liberties 
reported by those in attendance and depicted by the amateur video, 
which has been provided to all major local news agencies.

Surprisingly, the local Fox News affiliate 
<http://utah.indymedia.org/http://www.fox13.com>Fox 13 seemed to 
give the most unbiased report, stating that many attendees had 
reported excessive force, as well as showing the official media 
response from the Utah County Sherrif's Office. Clips of the 
previously mentioned video were also shown.

Other news agencies have gone along with the Sherrif's Office in 
painting a picture of drugs, guns, and sexual assault running rampant 
at electronic music events in general, and especially this one. 
<http://www.kutv.com>KUTV Channel 2 News blatantly inferred that the 
hired security was merely in place to prevent the sale of drugs by 
anyone but the event organizers. All major reports restate the claim 
made by the Sherrif's department that a 17-year-old girl was found by 
officers to have overdosed on ecstasy, treated on site, then released 
to her parents.

Many attendees and members of the electronic music and dance 
community are organizing lawsuits against the Sherrif's Office. The 
ACLU has been contacted as well as many organizations dedicated to 
educating and protecting the electronic music community. Vigilant 
party goers are compiling evidence, including video and pictures of 
the event, as well as personal accounts and documentation of injuries 
inflicted by law enforcement.

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

> 
> Police Raid Outdoor Music Event 
> by Parker Pinette Monday August 22, 2005 at 04:30 AM 
> ppinette@gmail.com 
> Numerous accounts from attendees of an outdoor electronic music event 
> in Utah county indicate excessive force used by Sherrif and SWAT 
> officers. A video has surfaced depicting officers dressed in full 
> military fatigues raiding the main stage of the event. Local news 
> stations side with police in initial reports. 
> 
> Attendees of the outdoor electronic music event dubbed "Versus II" 
> taking place the evening of Saturday, August 20th in the Diamond Fork 
> area of Spanish Fork Canyon in Utah County arrived at the event with 
> confidence that the concert organizers had obtained the proper 
> permits and legal clearance to hold the event. Personal accounts 
> available at the local electronic community 
> websiteutrave.org paint a scene 
> of police brutality and mayhem, many accounts bearing eyewitness to 
> the forceful arrest of young girls. 
> 
> Reports state that at approximately 11:30pm upwards of 90 officers, 
> many wearing full camouflage gear, gathered from Sherrif and SWAT 
> departments in surrounding areas stormed the previously peaceful 
> gathering dedicated to music and dance. At least 1 helicopter was 
> dispatched, along with large tranport vehicles designated for both 
> officers and detainees. Numerous statements from attendees indicate 
> excessive force being exerted by many officers. Inuries including 
> mild to severe bruises and cuts have been reported by party goers as 
> young as age 17. 
> 
> The Utah County Sherrif's Office has expressed a long term vendetta 
> against what they call "Rave" parties. Statements from the Sherrif's 
> office as well as eyewitness accounts make it clear that this was a 
> premeditated attack on the promoters and community supporting these 
> events. While the Sherrif's office has stated that many drugs and 
> pieces of paraphernalia were obtained, they fail to note how many of 
> the 60+ citations were for drug violations. Many accounts indicate 
> the majority of citations and arrests were for resisting arrest. The 
> Sherrif's office states that the party was raided on the grounds of 
> failure to obtain a mass gathering permit for an event hosting more 
> than 250 attendees. Reports vary as to the number in attendance, 
> estimation ranging from 250 to 1,400. Controversy exists as to 
> whether a mass gathering permit was actually obtained, however, a 
> Health Department permit was obtained, and hired security and 
> emergency medical service personnel were on site. 
> 
> Many eyewitness accounts indicate that officers singled out party 
> goers attempting to document the events on camcorders, cameras and 
> camera phones. Victims have claimed that officers knocked cameras out 
> of the hands of the owner, even confiscating some. Luckily, one 
> video has 
> surfaced, and is quickly spreading across the internet, as well as 
> being featured by at least one local news station. The video clearly 
> displays a large number of officers dressed in full camouflage 
> fatigues, some brandishing rifles. In the higher quality version of 
> the video, which includes sound, it is apparent that the use of a 
> taser was employed. While the video is somewhat unclear at times, the 
> viewer can plainly see an officer atop a young girl fully subdued on 
> the ground on her stomach; he swings on her at least twice, as more 
> officers rush forward to manhandle the girl. It is clear that many 
> others were subdued using similar levels of force. 
> 
> Initial reports from local news stations side with the Sherrif's 
> Office, one anchor calling the event a "drug party" without batting 
> an eye. Reports tend to focus on the drugs and paraphernalia acquired 
> by police, rather than the obvious violation of civil liberties 
> reported by those in attendance and depicted by the amateur video, 
> which has been provided to all major local news agencies. 
> 
> Surprisingly, the local Fox News affiliate 
> Fox 13 seemed to 
> give the most unbiased report, stating that many attendees had 
> reported excessive force, as well as showing the official media 
> response from the Utah County Sherrif's Office. Clips of the 
> previously mentioned video were also shown. 
> 
> Other news agencies have gone along with the Sherrif's Office in 
> painting a picture of drugs, guns, and sexual assault running rampant 
> at electronic music events in general, and especially this one. 
> KUTV Channel 2 News blatantly inferred that the 
> hired security was merely in place to prevent the sale of drugs by 
> anyone but the event organizers. All major reports restate the claim 
> made by the Sherrif's department that a 17-year-old girl was found by 
> officers to have overdosed on ecstasy, treated on site, then released 
> to her parents. 
> 
> Many attendees and members of the electronic music and dance 
> community are organizing lawsuits against the Sherrif's Office. The 
> ACLU has been contacted as well as many organizations dedicated to 
> educating and protecting the electronic music community. Vigilant 
> party goers are compiling evidence, including video and pictures of 
> the event, as well as personal accounts and documentation of injuries 
> inflicted by law enforcement. 
> 
> 
>

> "No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
> toward social justice or personal fulfillment. These sane and 
> enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
> sometimes knowing of each other but more often not. Socrates and 
> Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
> find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
> economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
> what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
> pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor." 
> -Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court. 
> 
> "Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
> the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
> gradually become visible." 
> -Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Synthesizer innovator Moog dies at 71

--0-1141117040-1124742551=:80445

Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

http://www.cnn.com/2005/TECH/08/22/moog.obit.ap/index.html
 
Synthesizer innovator Moog dies at 71
Monday, August 22, 2005; Posted: 12:03 p.m. EDT (16:03 GMT) 
 

RALEIGH, North Carolina (AP) -- Robert A. Moog, whose self-named synthesizers turned electric currents into sound and opened the musical wave that became electronica, has died. He was 71.

Moog died Sunday at his home in Asheville, according to his company's Web site. He had suffered from an inoperable brain tumor, detected in April.

A childhood interest in the theremin, one of the first electronic musical instruments, would lead Moog to a create a career and business that tied the name Moog as tightly to synthesizers as the name Les Paul is to electric guitars.

Despite traveling in circles that included jet-setting rockers, he always considered himself a technician.

"I'm an engineer. I see myself as a toolmaker and the musicians are my customers," he said in 2000. "They use the tools."

As a Ph.D. student in engineering physics at Cornell University, Moog -- rhymes with vogue -- in 1964 developed his first voltage-controlled synthesizer modules with composer Herbert Deutsch. By the end of that year, R.A. Moog Co. marketed the first commercial modular synthesizer.

The instrument allowed musicians, first in a studio and later on stage, to generate a range of sounds that could mimic nature or seem otherworldly by flipping a switch, twisting a dial, or sliding a knob. Other synthesizers were already on the market in 1964, but Moog's stood out for being small, light and versatile.

The arrival of the synthesizer came as just as the Beatles and other musicians started seeking ways to fuse psychedelic-drug experiences with their art. The Beatles used a Moog synthesizer on their 1969 album, "Abbey Road"; a Moog was used to create an eerie sound on the soundtrack to the 1971 film "A Clockwork Orange".

Keyboardist Walter (later Wendy) Carlos demonstrated the range of Moog's synthesizer by recording the hit album "Switched-On Bach" in 1968 using only the new instrument instead of an orchestra.

"Suddenly, there was a whole group of people in the world looking for a new sound in music, and it picked up very quickly," Deutsch, the Hofstra University emeritus music professor who helped develop the Moog prototype, said in a 2000 interview with The Associated Press.

The popularity of the synthesizer and the success of the company named for Moog took off in rock as extended keyboard solos in songs by Manfred Mann, Yes and Pink Floyd became part of the progressive sound of the 1970s.

"The sound defined progressive music as we know it," said Keith Emerson, keyboardist for the rock band Emerson, Lake and Palmer.

Along with rock, synthesizers developed since Moog's breakthrough helped inspire elements of 1970s funk, hip-hop, and techno.

Charles Carlini, a New York City concert promoter, staged Moogfest in May 2004 to mark a half-century since Moog founded his first company while still in college. Emerson, Rick Wakeman of Yes, and Bernie Worrell of Parliament/Funkadelic were among those who played, and a second Moogfest was held a year later.

Moog had "this absent-minded professorial way about him," Carlini said.

"He's like an Einstein of music," Carlini said. "He sees it like, there's a thought, an idea in the air, and it passes through him. Passing through him, he's able to build these instruments."

"A lot of people today don't realize what this man brought to the masses," Carlini said. "He brought electronic music to the masses and changed the way we hear music."

But the now-pervasive synthesizer's ability to mimic strings, horns, and percussion has also threatened some musicians.

In 2004, musicians extracted a promise from the Opera Company of Brooklyn to never again use an advanced kind of synthesizer, called a virtual orchestra machine, in future productions.

Born in 1934 in New York City, Moog paid for his studies at Queens College and Columbia University by building and marketing theremins, which are played by passing the hand through and around vibrating radio tubes. Theremins were used create the spooky "eww-woo-woo" sounds on the soundtracks of science fiction films such as "The Day the Earth Stood Still."

He went on to attach his name to a long list of synthesizers developed over the years -- among them Micromoog, Minitmoog, Multimoog and Memorymoog.

Moog, who had set up shop in suburban Buffalo, New York, sold R.A. Moog in 1973 and moved five years later to a remote plot outside Asheville, a scenic Appalachian Mountain city and center for new-age pursuits that Rolling Stone magazine once dubbed "America's new freak capital."

A deliberate man with brushed-back white hair and a breast pocket packed with pens, Moog drove an aging Toyota painted with a snail, vines and a fish blowing bubbles.

"When I drive that thing around, people smile at me," he said. "I really feel I'm enhancing the environment."

He spent the early 1990s as a research professor of music at the University of North Carolina at Asheville before turning full-time to running his new instrument business, which was renamed Moog Music in 2002. The roster of customers includes Nine Inch Nails, Pearl Jam, Beck, Phish, Sonic Youth and Widespread Panic.

Moog is survived by his wife, Ileana; his children, Laura Moog Lanier, Matthew Moog, Michelle Moog-Koussa and Renee Moog; a stepdaughter, Miranda Richmond; and his former wife, Shireleigh Moog.

A public memorial is scheduled for Wednesday in Asheville.

Off topic, just curious. Has anyone heard from Ravin Rizz lately? Is he still on the list?

I remember that he was busy with higher education, studying and whatnot, but I also remember what a good-hearted guy he was.

Rizz used to give massages at local underground parties (like Moksha Tribe) for his favorite charity, the Make a Wish foundation, and I thought that was sweet of him.

I mean, he would bring the whole setup--table, oils, etc. and instead of dancing/partying he would donate his time. When he did get a chance to dance, I  knew how much it meant to him (dance therapy) and he threw his soul into the steps.

What a guy, I miss him. I remember that he used to get so hungry, and one time I watched the table while he stepped out for McDonald's fries! Massage must be hard work!

 I'm sure he's still around somewhere, just checking!

Greg
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_11250_1124743591_0--

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: T.E.K. on KZSU radio tomorrow, 9a-Noon

If you're a fan of Armin Van Buuren then you should be sure to tune in
to KZSU, 90.1 FM, tomorrow morning between 9a and noon.  I'll be filling
in for the Unami Jazz Program, but I won't be bringing you jazz.  I'll
be bringing you someone who was totally influenced by Armin Van Buuren.
That someone is T.E.K.  Yup, he loves all kinds of electronic music, but
especially Trance/Progressive.  And Armin Van Buuren wasn't just an
influence for T.E.K., but the actual reason he started DJing himself
(after seeing Armin perform live.)  He still keeps on top of the world
of Armin through his weekly radio show "A State Of Trance."

With a background in piano from age 3, it's a given why T.E.K. prefers
the melodic trance side of things.  He also credits that musical
background with helping him in his DJ career.

Maybe he'll find success in his goal of helping to make trance and
progressive more of a success in the US musical scene.  Tune in tomorrow
and find out if he can!



http://www.jcthedj.com
AIM: jckzsu (or kzsudj during my show.)

Sometimes a little distraction is needed in order to see what is
waiting there for you.
- Baba Douglas

>
> Police Raid Outdoor Music Event
> by Parker Pinette Monday August 22, 2005 at 04:30 AM
> <mailto:ppinette@gmail.com>ppinette@gmail.com
> Numerous accounts from attendees of an outdoor electronic music event
> in Utah county indicate excessive force used by Sherrif and SWAT
> officers. A video has surfaced depicting officers dressed in full
> military fatigues raiding the main stage of the event. Local news
> stations side with police in initial reports.
>
> Attendees of the outdoor electronic music event dubbed "Versus II"
> taking place the evening of Saturday, August 20th in the Diamond Fork
> area of Spanish Fork Canyon in Utah County arrived at the event with
> confidence that the concert organizers had obtained the proper
> permits and legal clearance to hold the event. Personal accounts
> available at the local electronic community
> website<http://utrave.org>utrave<http://utrave.org>.org paint a scene
> of police brutality and mayhem, many accounts bearing eyewitness to
> the forceful arrest of young girls.
>
> Reports state that at approximately 11:30pm upwards of 90 officers,
> many wearing full camouflage gear, gathered from Sherrif and SWAT
> departments in surrounding areas stormed the previously peaceful
> gathering dedicated to music and dance. At least 1 helicopter was
> dispatched, along with large tranport vehicles designated for both
> officers and detainees. Numerous statements from attendees indicate
> excessive force being exerted by many officers. Inuries including
> mild to severe bruises and cuts have been reported by party goers as
> young as age 17.
>
> The Utah County Sherrif's Office has expressed a long term vendetta
> against what they call "Rave" parties. Statements from the Sherrif's
> office as well as eyewitness accounts make it clear that this was a
> premeditated attack on the promoters and community supporting these
> events. While the Sherrif's office has stated that many drugs and
> pieces of paraphernalia were obtained, they fail to note how many of
> the 60+ citations were for drug violations. Many accounts indicate
> the majority of citations and arrests were for resisting arrest. The
> Sherrif's office states that the party was raided on the grounds of
> failure to obtain a mass gathering permit for an event hosting more
> than 250 attendees. Reports vary as to the number in attendance,
> estimation ranging from 250 to 1,400. Controversy exists as to
> whether a mass gathering permit was actually obtained, however, a
> Health Department permit was obtained, and hired security and
> emergency medical service personnel were on site.
>
> Many eyewitness accounts indicate that officers singled out party
> goers attempting to document the events on camcorders, cameras and
> camera phones. Victims have claimed that officers knocked cameras out
> of the hands of the owner, even confiscating some. Luckily, one
> <http://homepage.mac.com/apexgrin/FileSharing2.html>video has
> surfaced, and is quickly spreading across the internet, as well as
> being featured by at least one local news station. The video clearly
> displays a large number of officers dressed in full camouflage
> fatigues, some brandishing rifles. In the higher quality version of
> the video, which includes sound, it is apparent that the use of a
> taser was employed. While the video is somewhat unclear at times, the
> viewer can plainly see an officer atop a young girl fully subdued on
> the ground on her stomach; he swings on her at least twice, as more
> officers rush forward to manhandle the girl. It is clear that many
> others were subdued using similar levels of force.
>
> Initial reports from local news stations side with the Sherrif's
> Office, one anchor calling the event a "drug party" without batting
> an eye. Reports tend to focus on the drugs and paraphernalia acquired
> by police, rather than the obvious violation of civil liberties
> reported by those in attendance and depicted by the amateur video,
> which has been provided to all major local news agencies.
>
> Surprisingly, the local Fox News affiliate
> <http://utah.indymedia.org/http://www.fox13.com>Fox 13 seemed to
> give the most unbiased report, stating that many attendees had
> reported excessive force, as well as showing the official media
> response from the Utah County Sherrif's Office. Clips of the
> previously mentioned video were also shown.
>
> Other news agencies have gone along with the Sherrif's Office in
> painting a picture of drugs, guns, and sexual assault running rampant
> at electronic music events in general, and especially this one.
> <http://www.kutv.com>KUTV Channel 2 News blatantly inferred that the
> hired security was merely in place to prevent the sale of drugs by
> anyone but the event organizers. All major reports restate the claim
> made by the Sherrif's department that a 17-year-old girl was found by
> officers to have overdosed on ecstasy, treated on site, then released
> to her parents.
>
> Many attendees and members of the electronic music and dance
> community are organizing lawsuits against the Sherrif's Office. The
> ACLU has been contacted as well as many organizations dedicated to
> educating and protecting the electronic music community. Vigilant
> party goers are compiling evidence, including video and pictures of
> the event, as well as personal accounts and documentation of injuries
> inflicted by law enforcement.
>
>
>
>

> on the net and elsewhere. Opinions are those of the contributors and

> "No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path
> toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and
> enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,
> sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and
> Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can
> find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and
> economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond
> what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative
> pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in
> squalor."
> -Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.
>
> "Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of
> the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will
> gradually become visible."
> -Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

> > inflicted by law enforcement.

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] Thanks to DEF for an awesome Sat night. 

I just wanted to give a party review and thanks since you rarely see party 
reviews anymore there was even a thread floating around about not seeing 
those anymore so here goes.

I rarely go out and even rarer that I play out but Chel-c and Sean asked if 
I was not busy if I could play so I jumped at the chance since I rarely get 
to play techno.

I was a lil pesimistic about a outdoor in the city since it gets so cold in 
the city but suprising enough once you got to the location it was average 
temp so I was not affected by it. I caught a bit of Sean's set and it was a 
groovy bit of minimal techno.. Then I was able to catch intergrated circuts. 
Now im not much of a live PA fan cause I think it looks a bit boring. Though 
I know doing an actual live PA must be hard as well but none the less it 
looks boring but these guys were laying it down on the minimal tip it flowed 
well a bit slow for a peak time performance but then again the crowd was a 
nice small mix. The DEF sound is always on par it was just loud enough not 
too loud or low just right. Next I was up at bat to mix and of course I had 
to take the BPM's up a notch  ;-)   So I played a drivy jacky type of techno 
set and im always amazed at how the DEF SF following is pretty much up for 
anything always a nice solid crowd not super big or small but always up for 
it. So I played a mix of hard and funky dancy type techno. After Myself was 
Andy and he was in Andy form with beat juggling,Scratching back queing etc.. 
He is really good at that type of chit!! only got to catch a bit of his set 
before it was time to head home.

Highlights were the Fire dancers people.. The clowns that showed up in 
costume and were grooving out that is very "Ravey" have not seen that in a 
while, talking to sean as he downs mucho beers I think he was a bit faded 
that was rocking to see since you rarely get to have fun at your own 
parties.

For those that may be on the "Fence" about techno parties or DEF SF parties 
I have to say you should check one out. It is not the type of hard pounding 
driving techno that most people think of. They book a good mix of techno 
some minimal, some straight up tech-house and others like myself a bit more 
drivey yet funky. They put a lot of time and energy into there parties and 
they are worth checking out at least once to get a full spectrum techno 
experience.

My hat goes off to them for trying to keep a UG sound alive and in the fore 
front.

Macadio

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Synthesizer innovator Moog dies at 71

ps Apollo already posted it.

At 01:29 PM 8/22/2005, CHUCK G wrote:

>http://www.cnn.com/2005/TECH/08/22/moog.obit.ap/index.html
>
>Synthesizer innovator Moog dies at 71
>Monday, August 22, 2005; Posted: 12:03 p.m. EDT (16:03 GMT)
>
>
>RALEIGH, North Carolina (AP) -- Robert A. Moog, whose self-named 
>synthesizers turned electric currents into sound and opened the musical 
>wave that became electronica, has died. He was 71.
>
>Moog died Sunday at his home in Asheville, according to his company's Web 
>site. He had suffered from an inoperable brain tumor, detected in April.
>
>A childhood interest in the theremin, one of the first electronic musical 
>instruments, would lead Moog to a create a career and business that tied 
>the name Moog as tightly to synthesizers as the name Les Paul is to 
>electric guitars.
>
>Despite traveling in circles that included jet-setting rockers, he always 
>considered himself a technician.
>
>"I'm an engineer. I see myself as a toolmaker and the musicians are my 
>customers," he said in 2000. "They use the tools."
>
>As a Ph.D. student in engineering physics at Cornell University, Moog -- 
>rhymes with vogue -- in 1964 developed his first voltage-controlled 
>synthesizer modules with composer Herbert Deutsch. By the end of that 
>year, R.A. Moog Co. marketed the first commercial modular synthesizer.
>
>The instrument allowed musicians, first in a studio and later on stage, to 
>generate a range of sounds that could mimic nature or seem otherworldly by 
>flipping a switch, twisting a dial, or sliding a knob. Other synthesizers 
>were already on the market in 1964, but Moog's stood out for being small, 
>light and versatile.
>
>The arrival of the synthesizer came as just as the Beatles and other 
>musicians started seeking ways to fuse psychedelic-drug experiences with 
>their art. The Beatles used a Moog synthesizer on their 1969 album, "Abbey 
>Road"; a Moog was used to create an eerie sound on the soundtrack to the 
>1971 film "A Clockwork Orange".
>
>Keyboardist Walter (later Wendy) Carlos demonstrated the range of Moog's 
>synthesizer by recording the hit album "Switched-On Bach" in 1968 using 
>only the new instrument instead of an orchestra.
>
>"Suddenly, there was a whole group of people in the world looking for a 
>new sound in music, and it picked up very quickly," Deutsch, the Hofstra 
>University emeritus music professor who helped develop the Moog prototype, 
>said in a 2000 interview with The Associated Press.
>
>The popularity of the synthesizer and the success of the company named for 
>Moog took off in rock as extended keyboard solos in songs by Manfred Mann, 
>Yes and Pink Floyd became part of the progressive sound of the 1970s.
>
>"The sound defined progressive music as we know it," said Keith Emerson, 
>keyboardist for the rock band Emerson, Lake and Palmer.
>
>Along with rock, synthesizers developed since Moog's breakthrough helped 
>inspire elements of 1970s funk, hip-hop, and techno.
>
>Charles Carlini, a New York City concert promoter, staged Moogfest in May 
>2004 to mark a half-century since Moog founded his first company while 
>still in college. Emerson, Rick Wakeman of Yes, and Bernie Worrell of 
>Parliament/Funkadelic were among those who played, and a second Moogfest 
>was held a year later.
>
>Moog had "this absent-minded professorial way about him," Carlini said.
>
>"He's like an Einstein of music," Carlini said. "He sees it like, there's 
>a thought, an idea in the air, and it passes through him. Passing through 
>him, he's able to build these instruments."
>
>"A lot of people today don't realize what this man brought to the masses," 
>Carlini said. "He brought electronic music to the masses and changed the 
>way we hear music."
>
>But the now-pervasive synthesizer's ability to mimic strings, horns, and 
>percussion has also threatened some musicians.
>
>In 2004, musicians extracted a promise from the Opera Company of Brooklyn 
>to never again use an advanced kind of synthesizer, called a virtual 
>orchestra machine, in future productions.
>
>Born in 1934 in New York City, Moog paid for his studies at Queens College 
>and Columbia University by building and marketing theremins, which are 
>played by passing the hand through and around vibrating radio tubes. 
>Theremins were used create the spooky "eww-woo-woo" sounds on the 
>soundtracks of science fiction films such as "The Day the Earth Stood Still."
>
>He went on to attach his name to a long list of synthesizers developed 
>over the years -- among them Micromoog, Minitmoog, Multimoog and Memorymoog.
>
>Moog, who had set up shop in suburban Buffalo, New York, sold R.A. Moog in 
>1973 and moved five years later to a remote plot outside Asheville, a 
>scenic Appalachian Mountain city and center for new-age pursuits that 
>Rolling Stone magazine once dubbed "America's new freak capital."
>
>A deliberate man with brushed-back white hair and a breast pocket packed 
>with pens, Moog drove an aging Toyota painted with a snail, vines and a 
>fish blowing bubbles.
>
>"When I drive that thing around, people smile at me," he said. "I really 
>feel I'm enhancing the environment."
>
>He spent the early 1990s as a research professor of music at the 
>University of North Carolina at Asheville before turning full-time to 
>running his new instrument business, which was renamed Moog Music in 2002. 
>The roster of customers includes Nine Inch Nails, Pearl Jam, Beck, Phish, 
>Sonic Youth and Widespread Panic.
>
>Moog is survived by his wife, Ileana; his children, Laura Moog Lanier, 
>Matthew Moog, Michelle Moog-Koussa and Renee Moog; a stepdaughter, Miranda 
>Richmond; and his former wife, Shireleigh Moog.
>
>A public memorial is scheduled for Wednesday in Asheville.
>
>
>
>
>
>
>---------------------------------
>  Start your day with Yahoo! - make it your home page

Macadio G. said:
> I just wanted to give a party review and thanks since you rarely see party
> reviews anymore there was even a thread floating around about not seeing
> those anymore so here goes.
>
> I rarely go out and even rarer that I play out but Chel-c and Sean asked
> if
> I was not busy if I could play so I jumped at the chance since I rarely
> get
> to play techno.
>
> I was a lil pesimistic about a outdoor in the city since it gets so cold
> in
> the city but suprising enough once you got to the location it was average
> temp so I was not affected by it. I caught a bit of Sean's set and it was
> a
> groovy bit of minimal techno.. Then I was able to catch intergrated
> circuts.
> Now im not much of a live PA fan cause I think it looks a bit boring.
> Though
> I know doing an actual live PA must be hard as well but none the less it
> looks boring but these guys were laying it down on the minimal tip it
> flowed
> well a bit slow for a peak time performance but then again the crowd was a
> nice small mix. The DEF sound is always on par it was just loud enough not
> too loud or low just right. Next I was up at bat to mix and of course I
> had
> to take the BPM's up a notch  ;-)   So I played a drivy jacky type of
> techno
> set and im always amazed at how the DEF SF following is pretty much up for
> anything always a nice solid crowd not super big or small but always up
> for
> it. So I played a mix of hard and funky dancy type techno. After Myself
> was
> Andy and he was in Andy form with beat juggling,Scratching back queing
> etc..
> He is really good at that type of chit!! only got to catch a bit of his
> set
> before it was time to head home.
>
> Highlights were the Fire dancers people.. The clowns that showed up in
> costume and were grooving out that is very "Ravey" have not seen that in a
> while, talking to sean as he downs mucho beers I think he was a bit faded
> that was rocking to see since you rarely get to have fun at your own
> parties.
>
> For those that may be on the "Fence" about techno parties or DEF SF
> parties
> I have to say you should check one out. It is not the type of hard
> pounding
> driving techno that most people think of. They book a good mix of techno
> some minimal, some straight up tech-house and others like myself a bit
> more
> drivey yet funky. They put a lot of time and energy into there parties and
> they are worth checking out at least once to get a full spectrum techno
> experience.
>
> My hat goes off to them for trying to keep a UG sound alive and in the
> fore
> front.
>
> Macadio

Subject: [sfraves] 2morrow Night  BREAKBEATS @ MIGHTY!!!!

Fine Cut Bodies
(Chi Recordings/Ritmic Records/Moving Target) Budapest, Hungary

As one of the founders of Chi Recordings, Fine Cut Bodies' tastes are broad 
and include all styles of electronic music from breaks to house to techno 
and experimental. His taste is guided more by his musical insight and not by 
any specific genre: he looks for music that is experimental but not selfish, 
interesting but not unlistenable. With the label, club night residencies, 
radio show and mixed-genre club mixes he is one of the most important 
trend-setting DJs in Hungary. Apart from appearances on the Chi Recordings 
label, Kevin has done a remix for the popular Hungarian band Quimby and 
worked on remixes for the Swiss label, Ritmic Records and the Dutch label, 
Moving Target. In the last few years, he has been a key DJ & promoter and 
has helped to develop a significant breaks scene in Hungary. His first 12 
titled "Deep Lack Of Balance" opened 6th on Muzik Magazines breaks chart 
and his remix for the Swiss Ritmic label called "The Boomspot" reached 4th 
on Mixmags breakbeat chart. More recently, Kevin's his latest release with 
EK & Spee, "Terminalhead", just reached 4th on DJMags breaks & beats chart 
and his "Trekk Far" single was picked by Uberzone for the Y4K compilation on 
Distinctive Records and remixed by Elite Force. FCB's tracks are continually 
being supported by top-level DJs such as Orbital, Plump DJs, John Tejada, 
Mr.C, Chris Carter, Hybrid, Laurent Garnier and Adam Freeland. Recently, he 
was awarded the title of Best Hungarian Breaks DJ from Impulse Creator, 
Hungary's largest internet magazine and his skills behind the decks have 
brought him around the world from Europe to Australia to the United States. 
Currently, FCB is in the studio working on remixes for Tipper and Carbon 
Community along with his next EP called Versus which will consist of 
collaborations with breaks heavyweights such as Chris Carter, Hybrid and 
Elite Force. We are glad to have him back in San Francisco once again, so 
come out support a good cause, and have a wicked good time.

a recent mix from FCB:
http://www.chi-recordings.com/angol/audio-mix.htm

Nubreaks Interview


Along with Bayarea dj's:

Greg J (KidBippy.com/Funky Cactus/Lotek)

Aaron Jae (Evil Breaks/SFBreaks.org/AaronJae.com)

Samira (Sister SF)

Mancub (Space Cowboys)

Hypnotech (Addictech)

Jay Vigor (StrategiK)

Jason Who - Sacramento

Bertzerker


Located at the world famous Mighty this show will kick off at 9pm and 
continue on till 2:30 am.


Bay 2 Breakin
@ Mighty (119 Utah, sf)
21+

Marc(O)
*THWAP!*//Moksha Tribe//Mario Bros.

I found this on www.craigslist.org and thought one of you may be interested...



---------------------------------

Stockroom position for dance music DJsReply to: anon-91489546@craigslist.org
Date: 2005-08-16, 2:52PM 

We are an online record store specializing in dance music on vinyl. We currently have one full time entry level position in our stock room open. The main responsibilities of this position involve preparing orders for shipment and putting new stock on the shelves. We are looking for a person who is not only enthusiastic about dance music, but who has a demonstrated interest in the music (i.e. you are a dance music DJ or make tracks, bedroom DJs / producers ok). **If you cannot demonstrate some level of interest in and experience with dance music, we will not consider your resume.**

While the entry level position does not require a specific knowledge of dance music in order to perform the duties of the position, we are looking for candidates who may have the potential to move into more advanced positions within our company, however, advancement is not guaranteed. We are seeking candidates who have an extensive knowledge of several genres in dance music - specifically house, trance, techno, and breaks. The ideal candidate should be able to identify and distinguish all major sub genres for each of these main genres of dance music. Additional requirements are: strong work ethic, detail oriented, work well as a part of a team. The position is full time Monday, 9-5.

Send resumes by email, No phone calls please.


Original URL: http://www.craigslist.org/eby/etc/91489546.html

Subject: [sfraves] Raving Is Not A Crime

------=_Part_73_13448992.1124843326892
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1

(This is something that's been brewing in my head for years and recent=20
events in Utah kinda made it all come out of me at once.... It's still in=
=20
raw form, and this is the second or third draft I've written in the last fe=
w=20
days but it's not quite there yet and I'd love some sort of feedback,=20
because i feel like I'm onto something. Thanks!)

Dress back jump back this is a bluebeat attack...
The British Army is waiting out there,
An' it weighs fifteen hundred tons..

The Clash, White Man In Hammersmith Palais
(Strummer/Jones)


right, right, this is totally a First Amendment, 'freedom of assembly' issu=
e=20
and hopefully when it comes time to challenge the Legislation enacted=20
against us, that will be the avenue to pursue.

I just did a long piece on why the authorities hate rave so much, posted=20
elsewhere, and it's not so much that they hate us as they are frightened to=
=20
death of us.=20

That's all because we are a threat to them in ways that one might miss if=
=20
one allowed themselves to get distracted by some surface shit that looks=20
like it's something, but it really isn't.

What really gives the authorities that set the rules for American society=
=20
today pause, is that in that every single minute we spend raving, it's=20
another minute that we are not eating their crap, buying their crap,=20
watching their crap, drinking their crap high fructose corn syrup crap=20
drinks, taking their addictive crap drugs, (ever seen someone try to kick=
=20
xanax? not very pretty.), etc, etc.

They just can't have that.=20

Might turn into something, over time, that they'd be powerless to control

That's why they're coming out with guns blazing against us the way that the=
y=20
do.

You ever notice, in a nation such as ours, how many morbidly obese, well,=
=20
let's just call them 'fat,' people there are?

It's an epidemic, by all accounts, isn't it?

Don't see a lot of fat people at raves, now do you?

Hint, that's probably got more to do with the dancing for 8-12 hours at a=
=20
stretch, than it does with juvenile wilding style frenzied drug taking, no=
=20
matter how many exposes FOX News Channel runs telling you otherwise.

Remember the emphasis they placed on 'the chill-rooms' when they were=20
crafting the laws against us?=20

How they tried to make them out to be some sort of super-sonic, electronic=
=20
crack-dens?=20

Smoke-screen.=20

It's bullshit.

This is where it gets into the whole Constitution, First Amendment, 'freedo=
m=20
of assembly' issue.

'Chill-rooms' are unique to raves, in that you don't really ever find them=
=20
in a bar or a club, and even if you do find an open space it's usually=20
crowded and noisy and difficult to talk in. The noise, heat and commotion=
=20
keeps the alcohol flowing which is the whole point.=20

But forget about having a heart felt one on one with anybody in that=20
environment

Chill-rooms aren't like that. They're actually a place you can go in the=20
middle of a hectic, chaotic party and well.... chill. You can hear yourself=
=20
think, mebbe relax a little. There might be other people there doing the=20
same thing, and since it's nice and chill, you might be able to start=20
talking with one another, peaceably and once you start talking, you might b=
e=20
able to start comparing life-notes with one another, and begin the process=
=20
of sorting out the crap from what's important in life.

This stuff, the relaxing, the thinking for yourself, the meeting of others=
=20
who are like you but different, and the sorting of the crap from The=20
ReaL....=20

None of this stuff sits well with The Authorities, cuz it gets right in the=
=20
middle of their game and they just don't like it.

If too many people go this way, all at once, it totally fucks up their=20
long-term business model.

Again, it's a THREAT.

I know this sounds a bit outlandish, but think this through.

What behaviors are supported and encouraged in this country, and which Shal=
l=20
Be Punished To The Full Extent of The Law?

Church and sports, both of which 'activities' more spectatorish than=20
participanty, where you'll be too busy facing forwards, and paying=20
attention, more to the game or sermon, than to yourself, or your neighbors,=
=20
to actually meet anybody, even if they're sitting near you, these activitie=
s=20
are OK in their book, but going out dancing all night, and, in the process,=
=20
maybe getting healthy and clear-headed, isn't?

What's up with that?

There's more to it than this, I'm sure, this is about what I've puzzled out=
=20
so far.

This is about economics, and power, and they seem to be figuring out right=
=20
now that if they nip this nascent movement in the bud they can cement their=
=20
position and hang on to what they've got for a long, long, long time.

I'm inclined to agree with them, since, well, they're the one with the=20
prisons, jails, guns, tasers, judges, courts, pepper-spray, helicopters,=20
cops, cuffs, legislators, riot-gear and pretty much complete control of the=
=20
media.

We certainly may not be outnumbered, especially in the long run, but we're=
=20
hopelessly and madly out-gunned, and completely disorganised and in all=20
sorts of disarray, limiting our ability to find any sort of voice for=20
ourselves politically, so, for the time being, this looks like a losing=20
battle.=20

They're going to keep comin' at us, full steam ahead, and there won't be=20
much any of us will be able to do to stop them.

The best we can hope for right now is that they get so exercised, they work=
=20
themselves into such a frothing, rabid, slathering apoplectic lather, that=
=20
mebbe some day they'll just plumb wear themselves out.

how you like dem apples?

> enshrined in the First Amendment. The laws requiring permits to hold=20
> public assemblies, including raves, are blatantly unconstitutional and
> un-American. The nimrod GI Joe wannabes who raided the event in Utah are

>To: SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>Subject: [sfraves] Raving Is Not A Crime
>Date: Tue, 23 Aug 2005 20:28:46 -0400
>
>(This is something that's been brewing in my head for years and recent
>events in Utah kinda made it all come out of me at once.... It's still in
>raw form, and this is the second or third draft I've written in the last 
>few
>days but it's not quite there yet and I'd love some sort of feedback,
>because i feel like I'm onto something. Thanks!)
>
>Dress back jump back this is a bluebeat attack...
>The British Army is waiting out there,
>An' it weighs fifteen hundred tons..
>
>The Clash, White Man In Hammersmith Palais
>(Strummer/Jones)
>
>
>right, right, this is totally a First Amendment, 'freedom of assembly' 
>issue
>and hopefully when it comes time to challenge the Legislation enacted
>against us, that will be the avenue to pursue.
>
>I just did a long piece on why the authorities hate rave so much, posted
>elsewhere, and it's not so much that they hate us as they are frightened to
>death of us.
>
>That's all because we are a threat to them in ways that one might miss if
>one allowed themselves to get distracted by some surface shit that looks
>like it's something, but it really isn't.
>
>What really gives the authorities that set the rules for American society
>today pause, is that in that every single minute we spend raving, it's
>another minute that we are not eating their crap, buying their crap,
>watching their crap, drinking their crap high fructose corn syrup crap
>drinks, taking their addictive crap drugs, (ever seen someone try to kick
>xanax? not very pretty.), etc, etc.
>
>They just can't have that.
>
>Might turn into something, over time, that they'd be powerless to control
>
>That's why they're coming out with guns blazing against us the way that 
>they
>do.
>
>You ever notice, in a nation such as ours, how many morbidly obese, well,
>let's just call them 'fat,' people there are?
>
>It's an epidemic, by all accounts, isn't it?
>
>Don't see a lot of fat people at raves, now do you?
>
>Hint, that's probably got more to do with the dancing for 8-12 hours at a
>stretch, than it does with juvenile wilding style frenzied drug taking, no
>matter how many exposes FOX News Channel runs telling you otherwise.
>
>Remember the emphasis they placed on 'the chill-rooms' when they were
>crafting the laws against us?
>
>How they tried to make them out to be some sort of super-sonic, electronic
>crack-dens?
>
>Smoke-screen.
>
>It's bullshit.
>
>This is where it gets into the whole Constitution, First Amendment, 
>'freedom
>of assembly' issue.
>
>'Chill-rooms' are unique to raves, in that you don't really ever find them
>in a bar or a club, and even if you do find an open space it's usually
>crowded and noisy and difficult to talk in. The noise, heat and commotion
>keeps the alcohol flowing which is the whole point.
>
>But forget about having a heart felt one on one with anybody in that
>environment
>
>Chill-rooms aren't like that. They're actually a place you can go in the
>middle of a hectic, chaotic party and well.... chill. You can hear yourself
>think, mebbe relax a little. There might be other people there doing the
>same thing, and since it's nice and chill, you might be able to start
>talking with one another, peaceably and once you start talking, you might 
>be
>able to start comparing life-notes with one another, and begin the process
>of sorting out the crap from what's important in life.
>
>This stuff, the relaxing, the thinking for yourself, the meeting of others
>who are like you but different, and the sorting of the crap from The
>ReaL....
>
>None of this stuff sits well with The Authorities, cuz it gets right in the
>middle of their game and they just don't like it.
>
>If too many people go this way, all at once, it totally fucks up their
>long-term business model.
>
>Again, it's a THREAT.
>
>I know this sounds a bit outlandish, but think this through.
>
>What behaviors are supported and encouraged in this country, and which 
>Shall
>Be Punished To The Full Extent of The Law?
>
>Church and sports, both of which 'activities' more spectatorish than
>participanty, where you'll be too busy facing forwards, and paying
>attention, more to the game or sermon, than to yourself, or your neighbors,
>to actually meet anybody, even if they're sitting near you, these 
>activities
>are OK in their book, but going out dancing all night, and, in the process,
>maybe getting healthy and clear-headed, isn't?
>
>What's up with that?
>
>There's more to it than this, I'm sure, this is about what I've puzzled out
>so far.
>
>This is about economics, and power, and they seem to be figuring out right
>now that if they nip this nascent movement in the bud they can cement their
>position and hang on to what they've got for a long, long, long time.
>
>I'm inclined to agree with them, since, well, they're the one with the
>prisons, jails, guns, tasers, judges, courts, pepper-spray, helicopters,
>cops, cuffs, legislators, riot-gear and pretty much complete control of the
>media.
>
>We certainly may not be outnumbered, especially in the long run, but we're
>hopelessly and madly out-gunned, and completely disorganised and in all
>sorts of disarray, limiting our ability to find any sort of voice for
>ourselves politically, so, for the time being, this looks like a losing
>battle.
>
>They're going to keep comin' at us, full steam ahead, and there won't be
>much any of us will be able to do to stop them.
>
>The best we can hope for right now is that they get so exercised, they work
>themselves into such a frothing, rabid, slathering apoplectic lather, that
>mebbe some day they'll just plumb wear themselves out.
>
>how you like dem apples?
>
>On 8/23/05, Myrple <> wrote:
> >
> > On Tue, 23 Aug 2005 11:58:13 -0400
> > "DJ Entropoopy" <> wrote:
> > > You know I'm right; the percentage of conservatives among the police
> > > force is almost ALWAYS higher, if not always higher, than the
> > > percentage in the given area. Duh. You have to RESPECT the law in
> > > order to enforce it.
> >
> > That's idiotic. The police are among some of the worst lawbreakers
> > around. This ranges from trivial crimes like using their emergency
> > lights because they dont feel like waiting at a traffic signal to more
> > heinous crimes such as this Utah raid. So the ravers had no permits...
> > so what? The idea of requiring permits for gatherings on public land
> > would have the Founding Fathers vomiting profusely. The freedom of
> > assembly was a huge element in their writings and discussions, and was
> > enshrined in the First Amendment. The laws requiring permits to hold
> > public assemblies, including raves, are blatantly unconstitutional and
> > un-American. The nimrod GI Joe wannabes who raided the event in Utah are
> > traitors to the Constitution and therefore criminals of the highest
> > order. Respect the law? They disgrace it, as do you by endorsing their
> > actions.
> >

> > >'Chill-rooms' are unique to raves, in that you don't really ever find
> > them
> > >in a bar or a club, and even if you do find an open space it's usually
> > >crowded and noisy and difficult to talk in. The noise, heat and 
>commotion
> > >keeps the alcohol flowing which is the whole point.
> > >
> > >But forget about having a heart felt one on one with anybody in that
> > >environment
> > >
> > >Chill-rooms aren't like that. They're actually a place you can go in 
>the
> > >middle of a hectic, chaotic party and well.... chill. You can hear
> > yourself
> > >think, mebbe relax a little. There might be other people there doing 
>the
> > >same thing, and since it's nice and chill, you might be able to start
> > >talking with one another, peaceably and once you start talking, you 
>might
> > >be
> > >able to start comparing life-notes with one another, and begin the

> > >of sorting out the crap from what's important in life.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Raving Is Not A Crime

Well I disagree. I think that 90% of people are trying to do what is
right, not only for themselves, but for the community. We all strive
for perfection. Perfection is God. Perfection is happiness, love,
peace, belonging, and euphoria. The other 10% are mentally insane
and/or filled with complete devilish hate. Yeah, some of the majority
may be ignorant or overly selfish and take away from the combined
positive, but in the end, everyone mostly wants what is right, and
right is closest to perfection.

The police and authorities are just trying to do what THEY think is
right. Save ravers from themselves. Save them from the bad. Save them
from the drugs, sex, death, and immorality. Save ravers from what they
don't understand. Yeah they are ignorant, but they don't have a hidden
agenda.

Likewise Bush, is ignorant. He doesn't have a hidden agenda, he isn't
evil, he just wants to do what is right and what is closest to
perfection. Unfortunately he is a complete idiot and shows it
everyday. Otherwise 1800+ soldiers wouldn't have died for an Iraqi
government that is less free and more dangerous (to US) then it was
previously under Sadam. Osama would have been captured, the illegal
boarder crossings would have been stopped, and we wouldn't be paying
$3.00 a gallon for gas.

This stuff is getting out of control.=20

How can we spend time fighting for raver rights when our friends will
be dead from terrorists tomorrow?
Who the fuck cares about Natalie Halloway?
Who cares about Michael Jackson?
Who really cares who Jennifer aniston is banging?
We are fighting for our lives here, can't anyone see that?

We can't pull out now. We must fight for what is right. But first we must l=
earn.

Maybe I'm a hopeless optimist, but I do see the good in 90% of the
people I meet.

Fire away.

Steve Osteen
http://www.tussinspace.com
http://www.myspace.com/stregansx

An Internet friend of mine who has been in the military commented  
after seeing the video:

The interesting thing is the thugs in Camo seem to be MILITARY not  
police.  It's difficult to tell for sure, I haven't looked frame by  
frame, but one of them seems to have a military patch on his  
shoulder.  And of course they seem to be carrying M16A2's; the  
standard rifle of our military.  So, if it IS the military, then  
they've already crossed some lines.

chilling.  I worry for those who are attending Burning Man this week  
and next.

was going on it was all Utah County Sherriff's department. About 90 in
all.

like a paddy wagon.'  Then found himself on the business end of one of
those guns.  He was then asked to leave and he said he was drunk (he's
over 21) so they said he could sit in his car and wait, then the cop next
to him told him to leave completely.

Howdy - long time lurker, new poster, constant dancer..
 
I feel you on the BM issue, as I'm leaving in a few days and had the same concern. But I don't think BM has anything to worry about yet for a few specific reasons that have everything to do with money and planning, which is what I think is central to the Utah bust.
 
BM is already lousy with authority  - there are local, county and state police, The BLM, the DEA and the ATF, Homeland Security agents and the Nevada Sheriff's department. They are both in uniform and undercover. They are camping on the grounds, they are watching you with night vision goggles, they are patrolling the areas with drug dogs. They are there for two reasons: to legitimately keep people 'safe' (such as looking out for date rape drugs, dealers and violence) and to make money for the state, the county and the Federal BLM.
 
>From personal experience, I can tell you that they are not looking to make arrests, because dealing with an actual arrest at BM is costly, time consuming and takes an officer off the playa and back to Reno, never to return. Unless you're carrying enough to be a dealer, they want to bust and ticket you, which accomplishes both their goals quickly. 'Safe' (save you from yourself) and money - here's your $250 ticket.
 
Part of the challenge, fun, whatever, of BM is having your cake and eating it, too, all whilest under the watchful eye of Big, Big Brother. This arrangement between LEOs and BM is that they can't take it too far, like swarming in with military raids and shutting it down, because they would lose an incredible source of income during that one week in summer (not to mention there are 20,000+ people there as opposed to 1,000 at a rave). As soon as the balance is tipped in one direction, it will cease to function. It's a very codependent relationship. BM needs to keep LEOs happy and provide stupid people to get busted (such as myself), and the LEOs need to keep it cool enough so stupid people will feel free enough to do stupid behavior in public and thereby enable a bust. 
 
This will last just long enough till BM becomes too hostile an environment for people to attend. I think it's inevitable that it will be 'authority' that will eventually end BM, and that's fine, because it will move underground again for 10 years till someone can make money on it again.
 
The Utah bust - well, I won't pretend that I know the full story, but I can guarantee you that if someone on the government food chain was making money on this event, it wouldn't have happened. It's unfortunate that the government can't see these things to be a money making opportunity, which is all they really care about. Rave out in the country, the state gets nothing - not even your tax dollars. Of course they hate it. The 'protecting the children' bullshit is just that - empty propaganda that hopefully most persons with a functioning cerebrum can see right through. Imagine the same event where they just calmly walked through confiscating and ticketing away, and let the event continue. That would be the smart thing, though it sucks to be busted. But at least you have the rave. But of course, this is Utah, and Bush's new Amerikka etc...wishful thinking.
 
Anyway, just wanted to post my 2 cents. These kinds of things chill me to the bone but I'm grateful to be reminded of how careful and diligent one must be in these trying times, whether your crime is better living through chemistry or dancing your ass off. Or both.
 
Hugs and kisses, KF

Subject: [sfraves] Sunset last Sunday...

This past Sunday I was lucky enough to be able to
attend the Sunset party up in Marin where I got to
meet two sfravers f2f...Adrianna and Osby.  Adrianna
your son is a handsome young man!  I am so happy I got
to meet both of you.

Osby you forgot to mention the highlight of your
Sunset getting to hold my baby boy Jack!  Yes that's
right I let Osby hold the little guy (he's six months
old)  Osby didn't drop him and he seems unharmed, but
I swear he keeps making a noise that sounds like he's
saying "reprazent" and then he starts bobbing his head
up and down wildly.  We may soon have to start feeding
hime pureed pizza for breakfast.  The breakfast of
champions! And sorry 'bout the grapes.  They were
moldy I swear!

I also met Michael Anthony and his very sweet
girlfriend Allison who was appropriately impressed
with my two youngest kids Ben and Jack ;)  You guys
are great!  Ronan I want the bubble pictures!  Check
out the information on their event this Sunday in San
Jose at http://www.house4thehomeless.org/index.htm 
Its for a great cause too!

It was great to see all the families out in the sun
listening to music, playing, and dancing together.  I
was excited to see Blakkat because I've dug so many of
his tracks and remixes and I own a few.  We have some
of the same records!  Days like this remind me of why
I got into this music in the first place.  It sure
would be nice to see open and family friendly events
of this sort continue through out the year. I'm
looking forward to Love Parade!

Peace,

Peter

---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

It was probably just police wanting to play with their toys.  Clearly,
this was an intimidation tactic.  So far, it looks like it is backfiring.

Someone called into Coast to Coast with George Nori last night who was
at the party.  They talked for a long time, it was good to hear a partygoer
get some good national airtime to talk about this.  George was in complete
agreement that it was scary.

-troy
