 giveways Too! 


~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  <http://www.velvetshop.com>

~~~~~~~~~ THURSDAY - August 25th:  SOLID GROOVES ~~~~~~~~~

    <http://www.mjgamez.com/velvetshop/images/augfront_web.jpg>
<http://www.mjgamez.com/velvetshop/images/augback_web.jpg>

One of the most well known and respected house events has been The Velvet
Shop. Created in the minds of M3, Loren, Rick Preston, and Mark Johns, The
Velvet Shop, to date has been the most successful underground platform of
the South Bay. Over the past 11 years, Mark Johns and M3 have brought in
some of the top tier DJs of the electronic music industry. Miguel Migs, Mark
Farina, David Harness, Ellen Ferrato, and Julius Papp have all graced the
tables at this venue.  Check out The Velvet Shop every Thursday at The Sofa
Lounge on 372 South First Street in Downtown San Jose.

This Thursday, August 25th The Velvet Shop proudly presents

SOLID GROOVES

DRU & DJ NOBLE

AND RESIDENTS:

M3 (Green Gorilla Lounge)

MJ GAMEZ (Velvet Shop / Global Sessions)

Check out The Velvet Shop every Thursday at The Sofa Lounge on 372 South
First Street in Downtown San Jose. 9:30pm - 2am

GUEST LIST good till 10:30PM.

To get on the GUEST LIST please send email to velvetshop@mjgamez.com

After 10:30pm only 5 Bucks!

Table Reservation and Bottle Service is Available.  For reservations email
reservations@mjgamez.com

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Artists Bios / Discography:

   <http://www.mjgamez.com/velvetshop/images/m3_web.jpg>

M3  Raising the volume of the Bay Areas nightlife since the early 90s, M3
has proved himself to be an influential character in the development of the
SF/SJ house music scene. Born and raised in San Jose, M3 began his music
career in 1990 promoting some of the original Bay Areas massives such as
Get Down, Get Down, Get Down, The Gathering, and Deep Space. Initially
influenced by music ranging from Rick James, Screaming Jay Hawkins, and Led
Zepplin, M3 began his d.j. career with a smooth down-tempo sound. Since
then, his sound has evolved to include a spectrum of thumpin house beats
which he is distinctively known. His dj name, M3, initially stood for
Marijuana Motivates the Mind, but has since transformed to Makes Me Move.
M3's funky fresh style will, without a doubt, have you moving by the end of
the night.

Today, M3 keeps himself busy with event promotions, music production, and
performing. M3 is spreading the good word of house from San Francisco to San
Jose, and beyond. Playing clubs in Moscow, Spain, Prague, Paris ,
Nottingham, New York, and Hawaii, M3 is funking it up all over the world.
Closer to home, M3 focuses his time on four residencies throughout the Bay
Area which include San Joses The Velvet Shop, SFs Green Gorilla Lounge,
2nd Sundays, and Le Boom. Pairing up with the Sunset Crew, M3 also co-hosts
the not to miss Fully Loaded party every other month.

M3 has performed alongside an astounding array artists including Marshall
Jefferson, Tony Humphries, DIY Sound Systems, Derrick Carter, Cajmere, Mark
Farina, Miguel Migs, Doc Martin, Jeno, Garth, Del the Funky Homosapien, and
Rick James. M3 can be found tearing it up in the local San Francisco scene,
djing in clubs, bars, and undergrounds all over the city.

Between playing and promoting, M3 has also established his own record label,
Green Gorilla Lounge. // www.greengorillalounge.com

   <http://www.mjgamez.com/velvetshop/images/mj_web.jpg> MJ GAMEZ  MJ Gamez
(GAH-mez) is from downtown San Jose, California and began his musical career
in the late 1990's. He landed his first residency with Global Sessions Music
created by Bobby Cruz and Sergio Aragones. His anticipated sets at the Red
Room and weekly FOXY event at The Cardiff Lounge quickly caught the
attention of the house community of the Bay Area. Quickly gaining
recognition for his unique sound and ability to move a crowd in the late
hours of the evening allowed MJ to land past residencies with Team
Bluefield, NLE, Club SPY, and special guest DJ appearances at 1015 Folsom
San Francisco, Sno-Drift, Paradise Lounge, and numerous underground events
in San Francisco. To date, MJ Gamez holds residencies with the 11 year
running Velvet Shop created by M3 (Green Gorilla Lounge) and Mark Johns (The
Velvet Shop), Global Sessions Music, Karma, and Sound Palette - Sounds of
the City. MJ Gamez is the founder of the San Francisco based Sound Palette -
Sounds of the City which has been held at 1015 Folsom San Francisco and is
currently running at Sno-Drift SF. Sound Palette has brought in talent such
as JT Donaldson, Rick Preston, M3, Chris Lum, Sharon Buck, Uneaq, Justin
Martin, Pete Avila, Nikola Baytala, Sharon Buck, Roger Moorehouse, Joey
Figueroa, Ivan Bautista, and Frank Zacarias. MJ also throws a weekly event
in his own hometown on Wednesdays at the Blue Monkey Lounge called Karma.
Karma is a platform for the upcoming artists, great local talent, and
national artists to spread great house music to the South Bay.

When asked how MJ Gamez began his musical career, he smiled big and said,
"What's so beautiful about the electronic music revolution is that everyone
can distinctly remember when that revolution began for themselves. For some
it began in a room as small as my garage where the music naturally flowed to
the soul. For others it began in a huge warehouse where the music hung damp
and heavy in the air and dripped down the backs of the crowd. My revolution
was brought to life in the mid 90's by Derrick Carter and Diz with their
special guest appearances in San Francisco."

In addition to his current residencies and numerous projects MJ Gamez
actively promotes electronic music of all forms by composing articles,
literary pieces, and artwork for AM+PM Magazine (After Midnight/Post
Meridiem) and the past In The Scene Magazine. AM+PM Magazine is a New York
style mini-magazine focusing on fashion, cuisine, music and the electronic
scene of the Bay Area. In The Scene Magazine was entirely focused on the
internal and external workings of the electronic music industry. Some
featured articles include:

AM+PM Magazine:
- Watering the Dormant Roots of Electronic Music in San Jose, Volume 1
- Electronic Music Steps Out of the Shadows, Volume 2
- Dig Deep to Hear What the Scene has to Say, Volume 3
- Changing Tides for a New Season, Volume 4
- Super Club vs. The Lounge Scene, Volume 5
- TOP SECRET...new venue opening in South Bay, Volume 6
- FAHRENHEIT Ultra Lounge - After Noon. After Work. After Hours, Volume 7

When people need to get out and dance, they are satisfying a hunger deep
within to release. It's precisely that hunger that drives people to find a
particular type of music that is unique, original, and yet speaks with the
commonality we all share within. This is the music MJ Gamez brings to the
industry and is called Home Grown Music. It's a sound that is organic, full,
and native. This music gets deep inside, feels comfortable, and brings you
to that familiar place. MJ Gamez has slowly developed this sound out of the
influences Inland Nights, Chris Lum, Diz, Derrick Carter, Mark Farina, DJ
Heather, Rick Preston, JT Donaldson, Spettro, and the Lawnchair Generals.

Keep a close eye on this up and coming DJ from the west coast. His
unrelenting drive, passion for music, and love for the arts allows him to
develop new and different styles of DJing, bringing a refreshing vibe to
Northern California. His unique blend of house music is defining an
international sound that awakens the ear and causes audiences to thump with
harmony. As MJ Gamez's musical career progresses, his influences continue to
evolve and transform as he constantly drives to expose the public to
different and beautiful music. With warm sentiment MJ ended the interview
with
I ultimately want people to have that experience that causes their own
musical revolution to begin."

   <http://www.mjgamez.com/velvetshop/images/sflogo_small.jpg>


Check out The Velvet Shop every Thursday at The Sofa Lounge on 372 South
First Street in Downtown San Jose. 9:30pm - 2am

she's bipolar, and taking LSD was the only time she's ever felt normal.  This is the second

need the acid for?'

one of the hottest after-parties in the bay.  And if you love breaks,
this will be THE place to be.

Brought to you by Evil Breaks, StrategiK, Funky Cactus, SFBreaks.org,
the Space Cowboys, and everyone with the Bayarea Breaks Brigade, this
breakbeat underground massive IS where you want to be.

For the Love of Breaks
A Love Parade After-Party
August 24th, 2005
Underground sf location
9pm-6am
info line: 415.267.1800

The main room with sound provided by the thumpin Addictech soundsystem:

Future Funk Squad (Universal/Default/en:vision) - UK
vs.
High Eight (TCR/Re:connect) - UK


Myagi (Finger lickin'/West/Pure Phunk/Splank) Toronto, Canada
vs.
Greg J (Funky Cactus/Lotek/Kidbippy.com)

Carbon Community (Sober Music/Bless Records) Dallas, TX

J-Break (Afterdark/Painted Puppy) FL

Samira (Sister SF/Seismic)
vs.
Aaron Jae (Evil Breaks/SFBreaks.org/AaronJae.com/Ill Behavior)

Ripple (Subscience)
vs.
Hypnotech (Addictech)

Jay Vigor (Strategik/London Breakz)

Bertzerker (Bayarea Breaks Brigade)


The upstairs area:

Odeed vs. Wish (Moonshine/W.E.) SoCal
Drag'nfly (Love Tribe/djDragnfly.com) Sacramento
A:dubl (Breakthru)
Murphstar (Seismic)
Bam vs. Marc(o) (Evil Breaks/Invibe)
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
Influence vs. Jason Who (Phunky People Project/StrategiK)
Erik Hz (Bayarea Breaks Brigade)

The Outside (but still inside area....you'll see):

THE UNIMOG

with all of the nasty little Space Cowboys we could find.

The Geometrist
Brad Robinson
Smoove
Mancub
8ball
Kapt'n Kirk
rrrus
Joy
Nicola

Need I say more?

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

House Music Awards 2005 - Nominees and Event Details


Well, it can honestly be said that House Music Awards are back purely 
by popular demand! The success of last year's spectacular inaugural 
Awards took everyone by surprise  the hosts included!  and it seems 
as though acceptance and support from industry, media and punters 
alike has quickly cemented the HMAs into the UK's dance scene. And 
now its back!

HMA 2005 kicked off with a very personal campaign to support Make 
Poverty History. Everyone from Pete Tong, Darren Emerson & Timo Mass 
to Bob Sinclar, Deep Dish and Ashley Beedle have been sporting the 
House Music Awards / Make Poverty History White Bands since Miami 
WMC. HMA was proud to support the campaign and thanks everyone who 
came on board to support too.

But back to important stuff!! The House Music Awards 2005 Nominations

Thousands and thousands of people of all ages and from all over the 
globe registered and voted online from March until the end of July. 
Find out exactly what they had to say in the Nominations listing 
below. Voting has now officially begun and runs until midnight on 
Thursday 27th October. And what about the party?

House Music 2005 will take place on Thursday 17th November, at the 
Hammersmith Palais.

Hammersmith Palais is not just a venue  it's a heritage. And it has 
been a creative epicentre for entertainment since its establishment 
in 1918. Originally christened the Palais de Danse to introduce Jazz 
to Europe, the Palais changed its name in the 70's and became a 
hotbed for Punk Rock, Ska and Reggae. The Clash named one of their 
most famous songs after the venue: "(White Man) in the Hammersmith 
Palais". The 80's and 90's saw all the biggest British bands headline 
with unforgettable appearances from the
likes of the Sex Pistols, The Police, U2, Primal Scream, Oasis & Ian 
Brown. Now heading back to its 'Danse' roots, and with a 
brand-spanking new Funktion 1 Sound System, the Palais hosts the 
House Music Awards 2005.

Dance all the way, baby!

HOUSE MUSIC AWARDS 2005 NOMINEES

ESSENTIAL SELECTION TRACK OF THE YEAR
Audio Bullys  Shot Me Down (Virgin)
Axwell  Feel the Vibe (Data)
Blaze  Most Precious Love (Defected)
BodyRockers  I Like The Way (Mercury)
Deep Dish  Flashdance (Deep Dish Records/Positiva)
Freemasons  Love On My Mind (Loaded)
Gadjo  So Many Times (Subliminal/Manifesto)
Martin Solveig  Everybody (Mixture/Defected)
Mylo  Drop The Pressure (Breastfed)
Sydenham & Ferrer  Sandcastles (Defected)


DJ Of the Year
Armand van Helden
David Guetta
Deep Dish
Erick Morillo
Junior Jack & Kid Crème
Louie Vega
Martin Solveig
Nic Fanciulli
Pete Tong
Roger Sanchez
Sandy Rivera


Label of the Year
Buzzin Fly
Defected
Eye Industries
Nocturnal Groove
Om Records
Positiva
Subliminal
Toolroom Records

Festival Event of the Year
Big Chill, Eastnor Castle
Coloursfest, Glasgow
Creamfields, Merseyside
Dance Valley, Netherlands
Escape in the Park, Swansea
Godskitchen Global Gathering, Stratford Upon Avon
Heineken Thirst, Sydney
Love Box, Clapham Common
Love Parade, San Francisco
Southport Weekender


CONTINUED:   http://www.dancefrontdoor.co.uk/article4518.html




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] Raids take the ecstasy out of Kuta raves

--=====================_1984390==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Raids take the ecstasy out of Kuta raves

Jakarta correspondent Sian Powell from Bali

August 27, 2005

MICHELLE Leslie has spent the past week hiding from the cameras - 
covering her face with a long piece of cloth and scuttling from the 
dingy lock-up in Bali police headquarters to the interrogation rooms 
and back again.

It's an undignified episode for the young Sydney-based woman more 
accustomed to posing for photographers. Stories swirl around the 
gamine 24-year-old underwear model: she has confessed to buying the 
two pills she was caught with, she was given them by a friend, she 
had no idea they were the illegal synthetic drug ecstasy, she has 
admitted to being an ecstasy addict, she has denied making such an 
admission and the allegations against her.

Whatever the truth of it, one thing is fact: Leslie was swept up in 
the huge drugs crackdown that began when Indonesia's new police 
commissioner assumed power last month. The former tsar of Indonesia's 
narcotics commission, national police chief General Sutanto has 
instituted a nationwide anti-drugs push. Police officers have been 
raiding nightclubs, taking urine tests from terrified party-goers, 
searching the handbags of ravers and patrolling known drug-dealing spots.

Across the archipelago another Australian, Graham Clifford Payne, 21, 
was caught up in the swoop. He was locked up last weekend in the 
western city of Medan after police officers claimed they found a tiny 
amount of methamphetamine or "shabu-shabu" in a package in his pocket 
and 2000 ephedrine pills and a used syringe containing traces of 
heroin in his rooms. Hauled in because police officers thought he 
looked suspicious, the Adelaide man has put a brave face on his 
arrest, saying he hopes to see his friends and family in a year or two.

If convicted, Payne faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison for 
narcotics possession and Leslie a maximum 15-year jail-term for 
possession of a psychotropic drug. Neither is likely to spend longer 
than a couple of years in prison, at most, but their arrests fuelled 
an outburst from John Howard: he couldn't believe Australians would 
be so stupid. At least 16 people from Australia have been arrested in 
the past 12 months on drug allegations. The Prime Minister's 
frustration may stem in part from the damage inflicted by a string of 
drug arrests during the past year on the once-genial relations 
between ordinary Indonesians and Australians.

CONTINUED: 
http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,16392809%255E28737,00.html




MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet: 
<http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

> be so stupid. At least 16 people from Australia have been arrested in
> the past 12 months on drug allegations. The Prime Minister's
> frustration may stem in part from the damage inflicted by a string of
> drug arrests during the past year on the once-genial relations
> between ordinary Indonesians and Australians.

"A human being is a part of a whole, called by us _universe_, a part limited 
in time and space. He experiences himself, his thoughts and feelings as 
something separated from the rest... a kind of optical delusion of his 
consciousness. This delusion is a kind of prison for us, restricting us to 
our personal desires and to affection for a few persons nearest to us. Our 
task must be to free ourselves from this prison by widening our circle of 
compassion to embrace all living creatures and the whole of nature in its 
beauty." -Albert Einstein

Sunday, August 28, 2005 ** House for the Homeless **

Come out and support HOUSE 4 The HOMELESS (H4H)

DJs: All Star Lineup

Venue: Club Deep, 87 N. San Pedro, SJ, CA

Time: 2pm - 2am

House 4 The Homeless (H4H) started as a group of friends with a mission, 
and is now an annual fundraising event designed to increase youth 
participation in the community and support EHC's Our House. On August 28, 
2005 @ Club Deep 87 N San Pedro, SJ, we will be hosting our fifth annual 
event. H4H is a one-day festival held at Deep Restaurant and Lounge in 
downtown San Jose involving music and dance, featuring some of the nations 
top djs.

Our volunteers are members of the youth community who are committed to 
making a difference. At House 4 The Homeless, we believe that the issue of 
youth homelessness is the communities responsibility to resolve. In order 
to achieve our goals, we need your support.

Last year we received media coverage on the Internet, local television 
stations, newspapers, and radio. This year we are committed to creating 
even more awareness and support through the media. As a patron of this 
event, you help make our community united, aware, and involved in the 
fight against youth homelessness. We value our sponsors and our patrons 
and consider you our partners in this event.

We hope that we can count on you to partner with us on this important 
community event. EVERYONE INVOLVED IS A VOLUNTEER AND ALL PROCEEDS FROM 
THE EVENT ARE DONATED!

Patio Loren Tamotsu Galen/Solar/J-Bird Michael Anthony & Late Night Sneaky 
Rick Preston

Main Room Stevian M3 JZ David Harness Garth

East Wing DJ Ara Mike Eversole N8 Castro MJ Gamez Harry Who?

West Wing DJ Deckster DJ Dougie Felipe Avelar DJ Seven Charlotte the 
Baroness Paul Leath/Chris Leath (2 x 4 set) DJ Dfunkt/Queen Agnes B (2 x 4 
set)

2PM to 2AM at Club Deep - 87 N San Pedro, San Jose. 
www.house4thehomeless.org 
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2250 
San Jose California, USA

Wednesday, August 31, 2005 ** Qool Rezzie Night **

Date & Time:  Wednesday, August 31, 2005 more on this date 5:00 PM 
Location:  111 Minna 111 Minna (near 2nd) San Francisco view map More 
Info:  www.qoolsf.com/ Every year there's this little get-together in 
Nevada called Burning Man. It is at this time of the year that we throw 
our annual "All Residents" edition of Qoöl. Why you ask? No, not because 9 
out of 10 SF DJs attend this little desert shindig, but because our 
residents deserve a night to themselves dammit! The cherry on this sundae? 
Qo?l LA resident Michael Scot in the mix alongside SF counterparts Hyper 
D, Gil, Scott Carrelli, and Jondi. Qoöl, qoöl, qoölio.

Lineup: 5-6pm Eiming 6-645pm Hyper D 645-730pm Gil 730-815pm Scott 
Carrelli 815-9pm Jondi 9-945pm Michael Scot

PM to 10:00 PM $5, 21++

Saturday, September 3, 2005 ** On The Rocks **

Date: September 3, 2005 (1st Saturdays)

Event Name: On the Rocks

Event Description: Would you like a Martini on the rocks?

How about some House Music "On the Rocks" instead?

AuraSF returns to the Alpha Bar for their party every 1st Saturdays. Their 
amazing and unique blend of House Music will take you on a musical journey 
into another world. Alpha Bar is no slouch itself as this new hip venue 
has been attracting a great vibe in San Francisco's Richmond District. 
Drink Special is Sailor Jerry's Spiced Rum and is one of the most popular 
drinks in the UK. Food served until midnight. Come down and check it 
out...

Come early to reserve seating!

9/3/05 We will have a Special Guest from the UK - Andy Newland

Andy Newland will also be playing at Qool and Anu while here in San 
Francisco. But you will get the first shot to see him. During his Fall US 
Tour, he will also be visiting Los Angeles and playing at Avalon and MNS. 
Be sure to check him out at one of these venues while he is here in the 
States. For more information on Andy, check out these websites: 
www.audiodeluxe.net and www.limitmusic.com

Our Drink Special is Sailor Jerry's Spiced Rum. Here is an excerpt from 
April 2005's edition of Stuff Magazine:

Unless you've got a battleship tattooed on your chest (and who doesn't?) 
you've probably never heard of Sailor Jerry~Wthe most famous tattoo artist 
of all time and the inspiration for Sailor Jerry's Navy Rum. Based on 
Jerry's own personal recipe, it's sweetened with a hint of cherry. It's 
also got a higher proof (92) than the average spiced rum, which may 
explain the cirrhosis that's tattooed to our liver. Hey, it looks like a 
swollen, bloated battleship!


Venue: Alpha Bar www.alphabarsf.com

Address: 3848 Geary Blvd. @ 3rd Avenue, San Francisco, CA

Time: 8pm - 2 am

Cover: FREE All Night, 21+ 
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2245

-------------------------------------------------
Administrative Notes
-------------------------------------------------

THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every week.

To subscribe to the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this list:
sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

If you have events to add to the SFRaves calendar, please publish them by
Friday @ Noon to be included in the SFR Calendar Weekly Edition Mailing.

SFRaves is a not for profit entity serving the Bay Area & all forms of
electronic music for 13 years.

Yeah, not so much the gun thing (what?)..but definitely to the term 'dropping'! Damn, that is true! My god, do people even still take LSD?  Sooo 80's! Lol!
 
And I have to admit that I do call prog trance 'washing machine music' - it just makes me feel like I'm having a seizure. I can't make my butt move that fast anymore.
 
But the main reason I know I'm old skool (and proud of it, ya' whipper snappers!)..
 
Because all the 'new' looks and fashion ideas that I see on the young'ens were things we were wearing in highschool! And honey, I won't even tell you how long ago that was - but suffice to say, everything comes around again in approximately 20 year cycles. 
 
Thinking fondly back on my first pair of creepers..goddamn, I was young and clueless. IMO, a few years under your belt does make it better. You have a little experience and a lot more emotional stability, not to mention your own money and a ride home.
 
Woohoo! Old skool! (off to take my glucosamine for healthy joints!)

Subject: [sfraves] Mini Review of Vote For Pedro

ok... I dunno.. I'm like totally mixed about how i feel about going
there... I'll start of saying that it wasn't what i hoped it would be.. I
mean.. I was all Mondo Yum on the fact that there was a hardcore party
goin' on!!  YAY!!!  Even more so 'cause Omar Santana was there & I really
wanted 2 talk 2 him again... but as soon as me & MOD got in there.. it was
ok...  no offense 2 the promoters 4 saing this... but it was basically
this mondo lame POSER candy kid e tard fest Palooza!  Seriously.. I Love
goin' 2 Hardcore parties where I mean... 75% of the people there are there
4 the music & dancin' their lil' booties off... but OK... every1 was
either standing/ walking/ sitting/ puddled out in the smoking area/ but
no.. there was no dancing @ all.. it was sad man... & it was kinda over
over over over over crowded..

I dunno who was spinning in the main room when we got there, but i did
like his set...  I did see Tronic & well... it was in passing, & it was
kinda quick, but he gabve me some Love!!  YAY!!  Then ummm... oh ohoh .. I
did talk 2 Omar, but the music was way 2 loud 2 have like this intellegent
conversation w/ him & didn't get 2 ask him about some things I wanted to
:(

I mean.. the people there were havin' fun & more power 2 them... I
dunno... I mean.. yeah.. i do go 2 candy parties still every so often
whatever, but uuuggh.. this was like I dunno... & I got these crazy mondo
weird vibes while we were there 'cause the enrgy was soooooo mu=ixed and
weird... I dunno... i just wan't done 4 the whole e tard orgy that was
goin' on & o h oh ohohohoh.. ok.. so this 1 girl was askin' me if she
could have a $1 so she could buy a pill!  I pretended not 2 hear her &
ooh.. I just wanted 2 cut her hair or something 'cause that reeeeeeeeally
pissed me off!  Hello 2day!  Uuuugh!

So after 20 minutes, we left...

But overall.. I did have a good night 'cause b4 that was Bam's suprise
party in the Mission & man, Brandon.. I Love ya 2 bits dude!  YAY!!!! 
Hello 2day... so fun!!!  It's always satisfying 2 get full off Sushi!

Hmmm... I'm confuzed!  I think i need 2 lie down somemore!

Thread-Index: AcWq2HwAKGK5X0HbR262p+yrBn/k5gAEeX/w
X-MimeOLE: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE V6.00.2900.2180
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Seattle is NOT San Francisco

I had better not forget this fact. I actually settled in Seattle, after
traveling through parts of the American West last summer, and I found a job
here, but it is not quite the same.

For one thing, there is no email list. Instead, there is a bulletin board
called Northwest Tekno, www.nwtekno.org, which lists events for the entire
Pacific Northwest including Vancouver, BC (Canada) and Portland, OR.

It does not have the listserv feature--something that I started to miss,
which is why I am still subscribed to sfraves.

Anyway, the music here is different, although drum n bass is popular, and
you have to seek out the underground by asking around. Russian trance is
also popular because Russians own several of the nightclubs.

On the other hand, there is not as much acceptance here for all lifestyles
and people. 

For example, when I first arrived in Seattle, I went to a club called Chop
Suey, met some ravers, and found out about an after-hours party. Then I
headed to Capital Hill, hung out at some bars, and met more ravers including
a nice Indian fellow. I invited him to the after hours party.

I danced in my usual freestyle fashion. We hung out in the chill room, I got
"fresh" but not vulgar and he got paranoid--it was a small screened off area
with a couch and a few chairs. Not highly visible but the lights were still
on because the after party was still getting starting. 

We left quickly--it was his idea to leave--faster than I have ever vacated a
rave, and he said, "Seattle is not like San Francisco." I remember these
words today.

Fast forward to Friday night. I checked out a new progressive house weekly
at Toi, a Thai restaurant in the Belltown district (downtown Seattle). The
music was fantastic, SF style--supplied by DJ Messiah from Spokane.
http://www.myspace.com/djmessiah

Party ended at 1 am, so I headed to the Palace Kitchen, a Seattle late-night
restaurant. 

I ate at the bar, near some drunken fellows, and I smiled at them in my
usual friendly style (not hitting on them--just being cordial). A couple of
the guys introduced themselves. 

Later, when I was leaving, one of the guys got in my face, aggressive,
actually grabbed me and kissed me in a "Tony Soprano" style, knocked my
eyeglasses to the floor in the process, and made lewd comments. 

I left the restaurant immediately, very upset, and I should have fought back
but I was startled and temporarily blind. I had to scramble to the floor for
my glasses or I would have been in big trouble. I felt like Clark Kent.

I wondered about my own actions and the power of alcohol on a person. I may
never smile at a stranger again. It was a restaurant, I was alone, and I did
not feel like being stony & silent because you do not meet people that way,
but I realized Seattle is definitely NOT San Francisco--Cheers everyone, I
miss you Sfravers.
Greg



---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Mini Review of Vote For Pedro

Osby, I feel for you, friend.=20

I remember going to a few parties like this one where NO ONE is dancing! =
It
blows my mind, too. I just do not understand--when I am feeling good, I =
want
to move my body. Maybe they are taking the wrong pills.

I always get people asking me if I have any pills or if I know where to =
get
some. You just get used to it--I was offended at first but I do not let =
it
bother me now, I just laugh or smile and say no, I do not have any.

I wonder, maybe if you are a dancer people think you are rolling.=20

I am sorry to hear about the bad vibes. I love happy hardcore. If I had =
been
there, I would be dancing to the hardcore beat, keeping YOU happy.

Greg

basically delineate based upon whatever. However they delineate, quotas, I 
think, vulcanize society. So I don't know how that fits into what everybody 
else is saying, their relative positions, but that's my position." George W. 
Bush (our president)

>From: "Greg Van Pelt" <gregvp@comcast.net>
>To: "'Apollo'" <apollo@speakeasy.org>,<sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>CC: <djmessiah@gmail.com>
>Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Seattle is NOT San Francisco
>Date: Sun, 28 Aug 2005 14:20:13 -0700
>
>I had better not forget this fact. I actually settled in Seattle, after
>traveling through parts of the American West last summer, and I found a job
>here, but it is not quite the same.
>
>For one thing, there is no email list. Instead, there is a bulletin board
>called Northwest Tekno, www.nwtekno.org, which lists events for the entire
>Pacific Northwest including Vancouver, BC (Canada) and Portland, OR.
>
>It does not have the listserv feature--something that I started to miss,
>which is why I am still subscribed to sfraves.
>
>Anyway, the music here is different, although drum n bass is popular, and
>you have to seek out the underground by asking around. Russian trance is
>also popular because Russians own several of the nightclubs.
>
>On the other hand, there is not as much acceptance here for all lifestyles
>and people.
>
>For example, when I first arrived in Seattle, I went to a club called Chop
>Suey, met some ravers, and found out about an after-hours party. Then I
>headed to Capital Hill, hung out at some bars, and met more ravers 
>including
>a nice Indian fellow. I invited him to the after hours party.
>
>I danced in my usual freestyle fashion. We hung out in the chill room, I 
>got
>"fresh" but not vulgar and he got paranoid--it was a small screened off 
>area
>with a couch and a few chairs. Not highly visible but the lights were still
>on because the after party was still getting starting.
>
>We left quickly--it was his idea to leave--faster than I have ever vacated 
>a
>rave, and he said, "Seattle is not like San Francisco." I remember these
>words today.
>
>Fast forward to Friday night. I checked out a new progressive house weekly
>at Toi, a Thai restaurant in the Belltown district (downtown Seattle). The
>music was fantastic, SF style--supplied by DJ Messiah from Spokane.
>http://www.myspace.com/djmessiah
>
>Party ended at 1 am, so I headed to the Palace Kitchen, a Seattle 
>late-night
>restaurant.
>
>I ate at the bar, near some drunken fellows, and I smiled at them in my
>usual friendly style (not hitting on them--just being cordial). A couple of
>the guys introduced themselves.
>
>Later, when I was leaving, one of the guys got in my face, aggressive,
>actually grabbed me and kissed me in a "Tony Soprano" style, knocked my
>eyeglasses to the floor in the process, and made lewd comments.
>
>I left the restaurant immediately, very upset, and I should have fought 
>back
>but I was startled and temporarily blind. I had to scramble to the floor 
>for
>my glasses or I would have been in big trouble. I felt like Clark Kent.
>
>I wondered about my own actions and the power of alcohol on a person. I may
>never smile at a stranger again. It was a restaurant, I was alone, and I 
>did
>not feel like being stony & silent because you do not meet people that way,
>but I realized Seattle is definitely NOT San Francisco--Cheers everyone, I
>miss you Sfravers.
>Greg
>
>
>

Well even some of the old school old-timer clans have fallen to=20
cronyism... "It's most important that our friends get to play." You go=20
to these events that once defined the underground scene, and guess what?=20
Hardly anyone is dancing.

Oh the clanmembers are happy (mostly) to be with their friends, and wow,=20
the DJ is sure happy to be there at an XXX event!... and unconcerned=20
that they've pretty much cleared the floor. Because, as a DJ, they suck.=20
Technical skill, varying, ability to make people shake booty? Hah...=20
Only a few really get it and can deliver. Do the people running the=20
thing get it?

When new peeps aren't interested into breaking into the tribe, and most=20
certainly won't be interested in the largely untalented "family" DJs,=20
then why will they come? Because XXX parties are "cool"? No emporer=20
walks naked unnoticed for long.

Burning Man (my first) should be an interesting test of this. It'll be a=20
motivating event, and we'll see firsthand what happens.

It's very tearing... on the one hand, I love my peeps, on the other, I=20
want to yell and be caught up in that vibe and the screaming crowds I so=20
well remember.

Sean

From: "Greg Van Pelt" <gregvp@comcast.net>
To: "'Apollo'" <apollo@speakeasy.org>; <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Cc: <djmessiah@gmail.com>
Sent: Sunday, August 28, 2005 2:20 PM
Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Seattle is NOT San Francisco


>I had better not forget this fact. I actually settled in Seattle, after
> traveling through parts of the American West last summer, and I found a 
> job
> here, but it is not quite the same.
>
> For one thing, there is no email list. Instead, there is a bulletin board
> called Northwest Tekno, www.nwtekno.org, which lists events for the entire
> Pacific Northwest including Vancouver, BC (Canada) and Portland, OR.
>
> It does not have the listserv feature--something that I started to miss,
> which is why I am still subscribed to sfraves.
>
> Anyway, the music here is different, although drum n bass is popular, and
> you have to seek out the underground by asking around. Russian trance is
> also popular because Russians own several of the nightclubs.
>
> On the other hand, there is not as much acceptance here for all lifestyles
> and people.
>
> For example, when I first arrived in Seattle, I went to a club called Chop
> Suey, met some ravers, and found out about an after-hours party. Then I
> headed to Capital Hill, hung out at some bars, and met more ravers 
> including
> a nice Indian fellow. I invited him to the after hours party.
>
> I danced in my usual freestyle fashion. We hung out in the chill room, I 
> got
> "fresh" but not vulgar and he got paranoid--it was a small screened off 
> area
> with a couch and a few chairs. Not highly visible but the lights were 
> still
> on because the after party was still getting starting.
>
> We left quickly--it was his idea to leave--faster than I have ever vacated 
> a
> rave, and he said, "Seattle is not like San Francisco." I remember these
> words today.
>
> Fast forward to Friday night. I checked out a new progressive house weekly
> at Toi, a Thai restaurant in the Belltown district (downtown Seattle). The
> music was fantastic, SF style--supplied by DJ Messiah from Spokane.
> http://www.myspace.com/djmessiah
>
> Party ended at 1 am, so I headed to the Palace Kitchen, a Seattle 
> late-night
> restaurant.
>
> I ate at the bar, near some drunken fellows, and I smiled at them in my
> usual friendly style (not hitting on them--just being cordial). A couple 
> of
> the guys introduced themselves.
>
> Later, when I was leaving, one of the guys got in my face, aggressive,
> actually grabbed me and kissed me in a "Tony Soprano" style, knocked my
> eyeglasses to the floor in the process, and made lewd comments.
>
> I left the restaurant immediately, very upset, and I should have fought 
> back
> but I was startled and temporarily blind. I had to scramble to the floor 
> for
> my glasses or I would have been in big trouble. I felt like Clark Kent.
>
> I wondered about my own actions and the power of alcohol on a person. I 
> may
> never smile at a stranger again. It was a restaurant, I was alone, and I 
> did
> not feel like being stony & silent because you do not meet people that 
> way,
> but I realized Seattle is definitely NOT San Francisco--Cheers everyone, I
> miss you Sfravers.
> Greg
>
>
>
> ---------------------------------------------------------------------
> To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
>
>

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Seattle is NOT San Francisco

Interesting.  I grew up in the Seattle party scene.  I lived in
Portland but would venture up to Seattle weekly, because they had
better parties.

Anyway, things must have changed since those days (94-99).  I remember
the Seattle crowd being one of the nicest and coolest crowds to hang
out with.  When i first moved here to SF i really had a bit of a shock
to find that at a lot of parties here were very cliquey.  People didnt
seem to mingle and interact a lot.  Groups would hang out with one
another spread out amongst the party, and people didnt seem quite as
friendly as the Seattle kids did.  It definatly took some time to get
used to, but then i stopped partying for a couple of years and when i
got back into it, it seemed to change again and it wasn't like it was
when i first moved down here in late 99.  I started to think if maybe
it was just the parties i was attending were differant then the ones
we went to when we first moved down here.  When i started helping out
with SWAT sound these last few year, and seeing the kiddie parties
again, i noticed that things hadn't changed.  It still seemed very
cliquey and quasi-thuggish.  I'm so glad i'm not in that scene
anymore, it seems really alien to me, and the crowds at the Otherworld
parties, FnF parties and such are much more like what i was used to in
 Seattle.  Everyone is willing to talk to one another, new friends are
made at every event...that sort of stuff.  Maybe it's just these club
type functions going on in Seattle...definatly seek out the
underground stuff.  Or venture down to Portland once in a while.  The
underground there still seems pretty much the same, at least the last
time i was up there a couple of years ago.

--=20
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

--- Greg Van Pelt <gregvp@comcast.net> wrote:

> I had better not forget this fact. I actually
> settled in Seattle, after
> traveling through parts of the American West last
> summer, and I found a job
> here, but it is not quite the same.
> 
> For one thing, there is no email list. Instead,
> there is a bulletin board
> called Northwest Tekno, www.nwtekno.org, which lists
> events for the entire
> Pacific Northwest including Vancouver, BC (Canada)
> and Portland, OR.
> 
> It does not have the listserv feature--something
> that I started to miss,
> which is why I am still subscribed to sfraves.
> 
> Anyway, the music here is different, although drum n
> bass is popular, and
> you have to seek out the underground by asking
> around. Russian trance is
> also popular because Russians own several of the
> nightclubs.
> 
> On the other hand, there is not as much acceptance
> here for all lifestyles
> and people. 
> 
> For example, when I first arrived in Seattle, I went
> to a club called Chop
> Suey, met some ravers, and found out about an
> after-hours party. Then I
> headed to Capital Hill, hung out at some bars, and
> met more ravers including
> a nice Indian fellow. I invited him to the after
> hours party.
> 
> I danced in my usual freestyle fashion. We hung out
> in the chill room, I got
> "fresh" but not vulgar and he got paranoid--it was a
> small screened off area
> with a couch and a few chairs. Not highly visible
> but the lights were still
> on because the after party was still getting
> starting. 
> 
> We left quickly--it was his idea to leave--faster
> than I have ever vacated a
> rave, and he said, "Seattle is not like San
> Francisco." I remember these
> words today.
> 
> Fast forward to Friday night. I checked out a new
> progressive house weekly
> at Toi, a Thai restaurant in the Belltown district
> (downtown Seattle). The
> music was fantastic, SF style--supplied by DJ
> Messiah from Spokane.
> http://www.myspace.com/djmessiah
> 
> Party ended at 1 am, so I headed to the Palace
> Kitchen, a Seattle late-night
> restaurant. 
> 
> I ate at the bar, near some drunken fellows, and I
> smiled at them in my
> usual friendly style (not hitting on them--just

> the guys introduced themselves. 
> 
> Later, when I was leaving, one of the guys got in my
> face, aggressive,
> actually grabbed me and kissed me in a "Tony
> Soprano" style, knocked my
> eyeglasses to the floor in the process, and made
> lewd comments. 
> 
> I left the restaurant immediately, very upset, and I
> should have fought back
> but I was startled and temporarily blind. I had to
> scramble to the floor for
> my glasses or I would have been in big trouble. I
> felt like Clark Kent.
> 
> I wondered about my own actions and the power of
> alcohol on a person. I may
> never smile at a stranger again. It was a
> restaurant, I was alone, and I did
> not feel like being stony & silent because you do
> not meet people that way,
> but I realized Seattle is definitely NOT San
> Francisco--Cheers everyone, I
> miss you Sfravers.
> Greg
> 
>

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  Request for QA Opportunities in Open Source Projects, Employment,
 Full-Time, Contract, Consulting Roles

Request for QA Opportunities in Open Source Projects, Employment, 
Full-Time, Contract, Consulting Roles

I'm seeking interesting Full Time, Contract, Consulting/Freelance 
Opportunities *and* Open Source Projects that are looking for a QA 
engineer with a solid background and diverse technical skillset. I've been 
in Software / Hardware Quality Assurance for 12+ years and am seeking 
projects to contribute towards the quality of the Gnu Public license 
and/or any Open Source model. I also am interested in Full-time 
employment, contract/consulting roles, as well as part-time/freelance work 
on any projects that seek a stellar QA engineer. If you know of someone 
who needs help or is looking for a tester with a technical edge, please 
feel free to refer them to me.

Summary & Qualifications: 12 years experience in Hardware/Software QA 
Engineering, Product and Technical Support.
- 7 years experience managing Quality Assurance organizations, leading 
multiple QA engineers and projects.
- 12 years experience in a QA Engineer role, 11 years experience in a 
Senior QA Engineer and Lead QA Engineer role.
- 12 years experience providing Technical, Product & QA Support for small 
& large companies, products & networks.
- 12 years experience establishing various QA processes and procedures 
including: Product Development and Software LifeCycle, the QA Lifecycle 
process, Defect Submittal, Reporting, Tracking and Escalation Lifecycle, 
Product Validation, Certification and Release Lifecycle, QA Project 
Planning, QA Test Methodologies and Processes.
- 12 years experience implementing and designing schemas for Defect 
Tracking Systems.
- 8 years experience in a Product Support and Technical Support 
Engineering role.
- 8 years experience establishing and improving Technical and Product 
Support issues and procedures.
- 12 Years planning and executing Test Plans as part of the design, 
development and QA cycle of various projects.
- 12 years experience authoring and conducting Acceptance, Ad-Hoc, Black 
Box (Behavioral, Functional, Closed Box, Opaque box), GUI, Functional, 
Integration, Installation, Manual, Navigation, Module and Regression 
Tests.
- 11 Years performing release certification and validation, Unit and 
Integration Checks, Source Code Management.
- 10 years conducting White Box tests (Structural, Glassbox, Clearbox, 
System Internals, Branch/Path Coverage Tests).
- 12 years authoring and executing Performance, Database, Security, 
Smokescreen, Stress, Boundary, Load, Validation, SW & HW Compatibility 
Tests using advanced and innovative Test Methodologies in Macintosh, 
Windows, Unix, WAP, WML, Wireless, Console game systems and Palm OS 
environments.
- 12 years authoring, documenting/defining standards for QA (Checklists, 
Configuration Management, Status Reports, Test Plans, Test Cases, Test 
Diagrams, Testing Metrics, Test Planning/Strategy, Test Scripts and Test 
Procedures).
- 7 years experience administrating QA Lab Operations (Network/Test/Lab 
Environment), QA Release Cycle and QA Intranet website. Functions of this 
capacity included: QA Website Webmaster, QA Lab Administrator, QA 
Production Lab Administrator, QA Release certification and Defect Tracking 
Systems Administrator.
- Proven expertise in Troubleshooting / Problem-solving, as individual or 
cross-functionally.
- Proficient knowledge of advanced testing methodologies and techniques.
- Fluent in the processes of requirements development, software code 
reviews, change control and configuration.

Complete Resume, Professional Referrals, References and Recommendations 
available upon request.

Psychic Blast

Subject: [sfraves] unfair. was: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Seattle is NOT San Francisco

greg wrote:

> I had better not forget this fact. I actually settled in Seattle, after
> traveling through parts of the American West last summer, and I found a
> job
> here, but it is not quite the same.
>
> For one thing, there is no email list. Instead, there is a bulletin board
> called Northwest Tekno, www.nwtekno.org, which lists events for the entire
> Pacific Northwest including Vancouver, BC (Canada) and Portland, OR.


hi! i'm kim. i am the admin for the nw-raves website on hyperreal, which
has been around since 1993. its website and directions for subscribing to
its email list are at http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/nw . if you're ever
travelling to another part of the country and seeking a mailing list on
hyperreal, the regional mailing lists are all linked at
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves

i also run the nwtekno website, but it was never intended to replace nwr.
i started it to get some print ads for a zine i was starting, scene not
herd. hardly anyone from vancouver uses it, so i wouldn't recommend it as
a good source for vancouver info (i do adore vancouver tho and recommend
that you visit if you haven't)


> On the other hand, there is not as much acceptance here for all lifestyles
> and people.


i freely admit my bias: i've been dancing at/facilitating events here for
~12 years and am pretty fond of the city ;)

but from my perspective your generalizations are sweeping & inaccurate. if
you go to belltown, of course you're gonna get weird behavior. i can't
name the corresponding area of sf 'cause i'm not that familiar with the
city, but think of whatever part of sf you'd refer to as "meat market
central" and there you go.

seems to me like every city has some places that are wack and some that
are fantastic, and so i consider it the responsibility of the tourist
and/or inhabitant to research which are which before choosing an event to
attend and/or passing judgement on the city.

what exactly did you mean by saying that you were getting "fresh but not
vulgar" with the indian fellow prior to him freaking out and informing you
that "seattle is not san francisco"? you noted that your behavior in the
chill room was "not highly visible"... what is it that you were doing with
the indian man that you wouldn't necessarily want to be highly visible? :P
perhaps his resulting anxiety might not have been directly connected to
anything specific to seattle? also, although we do have a sizable indian
community, i wouldn't necessarily assume that he was born & raised here
unless he'd said so... so it doesn't seem fair to assume that he
represents "seattle" behavior.

anyway, if you want recommendations of events to attend and/or places to
go that the natives consider quality, feel free to email and/or im me.. my
preferred im program is the new google talk and i'm makeitfunkynow at
gmail.com on there.

i'd recommend the following to anyone & everyone visiting the city

http://www.decibelfestival.com
http://www.bumbershoot.org
http://www.central-cinema.com
http://www.mcphee.com

ymmv, of course ;)

kim
http://www.to-evolve.com

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: EKLEKTIC  * YR OLD BDAY SHINDIG: 1015: RONI SIZE

To veiw thread, go 2 www.groundscore.net, click flyer, then go to DNB
events (sorry... 2 lazy 2 cut & past link.. LoL.. Hello 2day)

Eklektic Turns 8 / Fuck Off And Dance

What began in 1997 as three girls' party-with-heart, San Francisco's
infamous Eklektic, lived up to its name for the five years that it ran as
a weekly. A drum & bass night at the core, Eklektic developed to involve
everything from dub to disco to hip hop to 'ardcore to 2- step to breaks.

With a strong foundation in local talent and tough rank of residents,
Eklektic and its production company, Groundscore, brought top-shelf sounds
to a warm and enthusiastic reception in the "red light district" of their
dancefloor.

There are few headliners who have yet to grace the decks over the years as
the party has lived on as a series of one-offs. Roni Size, however, is one
of them, and September 2 marks Eklektic's 8 Year Anniversary by showcasing
the one who can truly reprazent. Groundscore welcomes the opportunity to
introduce one unmistakable vibe to another. Not to be missed!

Eklektic's 8 Year Anniversary with Roni Size, Gridlok, 4Real, Mal, Audio
Angel, MCs Duh & Colonel, Felix the Dog, Rascue, and Jamin. September 2,
2005 / Doors open at 10pm / 1015 Folsom at 6th St.

Presales are $15... $20 @ door... see U on the floor!  Oh oh ohoh oh ..
yeah.. & I got a Groovy new outfit I custom made myself (short shoes,
shirt & a jacket from Target) that i'll be wearing that day!! YAY!!  I
kinda broke my own promise & I broke in my shoes last SaT 4 Bam 'cause I
<3 my Bro!!  But yeah... if you're not gonna be @ BM or Mezzanine.. come 1
1015... you'll have soo much fun!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] "Silent" disco?

I don't think I could get into that, nor most people. The thing about
clubbing and a bunch of people dancing together to a common beat is
the cohesion of people interacting with each other and the music
together. During a breakdown, the sound of people yelling, whistling,
and feeling the music together rubs off on everyone collectively
bringing the energy up. Just listen to a mix CD like Tiesto Magik #6
which was recorded live with all the sound of the audience and compare
it to a studio mix CD like Tiesto Summerbreeze.  Both are
masterpieces, but Magik 6 actually brings me to non drug affected
tears with chills running down my spine during the Delerium - Silence
(tiesto rmx) breakdown as you hear the absolute euphoric yells of the
crowd. On Summerbreeze the same breakdown merely makes me a little
reflective.

Also, bass is something you need to feel, not just hear.

Speaking of getting high off music, read this:

Ok, here is the absolute key to trancing out to trance without using drugs:

1. Sit near an air conditioner and have it running a little colder then usu=
al
2. Turn out the lights
3. PLAY THE MUSIC LOUD (I mean as high as you can without ear damage)
preferably with a bass that rumbles your chest.
4. Clear your mind of all your current problems in life(don't bs me,
everyone has problems)
5. Think about happy stuff, so maybe for you, what this track would
feel like in a crowded club played by your favorite DJ while everyone
is rolling and feeling the same exact vibe as you.
6. Throw your arms in the air and yell at the top of your lungs
durring the build up.
7. Dance and Feel the fucking music
8. If all else fails, listen to harder music

Most of these can be done in the car, but you better not loose your
concetration on the road. Crashes have happened because of trance
before.

I wrote that a few years ago for tranceaddict. Yeah, well, so I like trance=
.

Steve Osteen


=20

> > durring the build up.

Subject: [sfraves] Raves: The End of an Era

--0-1997005585-1125360954=:64698
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8BIT


Source: http://www.raves.com/features/show/31/THERAVESERA

  Written by Shawn Wallace

As society changes there are things that will always stand the test of 
time. Each passing generation makes their mark in the best way that they 
know and leave behind the markers of their era. Rave parties are the sort 
an event that brought people together through a common shared interest in 
music and community. The raves were a cultural movement that also defined 
an era in the progression of DJ and club culture.

>From Outlaw To Main Stage

Being involved in the scene has always held a special place for a person. 
Whether it has been scouting out a location for an outlaw party in the 
early days, scribbling out that first handwritten version of the flyer 
that would get the crowds to the site, or trying to find out the best way 
to get power to two turntables in the middle of the woods for hours. In 
the early days, word of mouth was the only way that you could find out 
anything about a rave. You had to know someone who knew someone was who 
was trusted by someone throwing the party to have any chance of knowing 
where to go. Rave parties began as a place where pure enjoyment was driven 
by the music. It wasn't about the outfit you wore or who you knew, it was 
letting the DJ manning the decks take you through an amazing journey 
driven by the ebb and flow of beats and basslines. Standing in lines at 
the parties waiting to drop your five bucks and get your wristband, you 
would notice the diversity of the crowd that was drawn to the events. 
People of all races, genders, sexual orientation, and social standing 
could be found intermixed among the flashing lights and pulsing beats 
moving to one universal groove. As the scene began to grow, dance music 
fans looked for alternative means to get information about the best music, 
raves, and clubs. Much of this coming together was accomplished through 
the internet with websites, such as the aptly-titled Raves.com, 
DJ/electronic culture magazines, like BPM, XLR8R, and Mixmag, chat rooms, 
and boards all became an essential piece of the global takeover by raves 
and dance music.

The Mainstream Didn't Know What Hit Them

As the scene began to expand and more people became involved in the 
process, it was only a matter of time before the mainstream would begin to 
take notice. Suddenly, the rave party was everywhere. It was the place to 
be seen. Kids in day-glo outfits sucking on candy-canes became almost a 
punchline in youth-oriented films coming from Hollywood, the remix became 
the ultimate vehicle for a mainstream artist to gain instant credibility 
with the clubbing elite, and the turntable took over the guitar as the 
must have instrument for the new generation. The biggest sign of the rave 
breakthrough was the birth of the cult of the Superstar DJ, who went from 
being an unknown face in the back of the room just Ñplaying recordsâ to an 
instant celebrity whose selection of music and tastes could make or beak a 
nightclubÇs future. Finding out where the parties were being held became 
less of an investigation and more of an artistic venture as the club flyer 
took an amazing turn and became an expression of the theme of the 
impending event.

The Fall After The Rise

In a move that has become typical of any growing youth-based movement, the 
politicians of the day decided to step in and try to use the rave party as 
a tool to garner support for their own grandiose agendas at the expense of 
the clubbers. Never taking into mind the creative DJs, musicians, artists, 
promoters, and fans who made up the community surrounding these events. 
This move may have impacted the mainstream exposure of the events, but 
only drove the people behind the scene back into the underground, back to 
where it all began. The move by politicians to focus on the negative sides 
of the rave party phenomenon only drove the fans of the culture together 
and created a tighter unit.

On the heels of some long, well-fought battles by the clubbing community, 
we made some progress. In the end though, we have seen the rave party 
slowly fade into a distant memory. As superclubs began to focus theme 
nights around DJs and getting numbers in the doors, somewhere along the 
way the party became secondary to creating the next big marketing brand. 
For those of use who were there, raves are a memory that will last 
forever. They were our search for the supernatural and divine place where 
we all come together and one thing is inecapable... we will always have 
the music.


--

If there is a sin against life, it consists perhaps not so
much in despairing of life as in hoping for another life
& in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.
-- Albert Camus -- *******************************************

the first time i heard of Tiesto was around 2000 and i got hooked on his In=
=20
Search for Sunrise mix. i still think it's a good mix. perfect for listenin=
g=20
to while driving home in the morning after a party. pretty mellow, melodic=
=20
trance. had a nice flow to it. (of course, in 2000 i also thought that=20
Thomas Trouble was a great DJ)

first time i heard Tiesto was around 2000-2001 at 1015. i thought he was=20
good. the music was pretty jammin' as far as trance goes and the room was=
=20
rockin.

then the mixes i was downloading seemed to get less interesting. borderline=
=20
boring for me. by 2002 people who had no base in underground dance music or=
=20
electronic music in general were on tiesto's jock. i saw him at mezzanine=
=20
around 2003 and he was pretty lame. dj diva. i just don't think the guy is=
=20
worth the hype. he's a good dj.

but from what i've experienced hearing him live and listening to his mixes,=
=20
he's just not anything extra-ordinary.

except for that In Search for Sunrise mix. that was pretty good. might be=
=20
better if i turned off the lights and stood infront of the air conditioner?

> the cohesion of people interacting with each other
> and the music
> together. During a breakdown, the sound of people
> yelling, whistling,
> and feeling the music together rubs off on everyone
> collectively
> bringing the energy up. Just listen to a mix CD like
> Tiesto Magik #6
> which was recorded live with all the sound of the
> audience and compare
> it to a studio mix CD like Tiesto Summerbreeze. 
> Both are
> masterpieces, but Magik 6 actually brings me to non
> drug affected
> tears with chills running down my spine during the
> Delerium - Silence
> (tiesto rmx) breakdown as you hear the absolute
> euphoric yells of the
> crowd. On Summerbreeze the same breakdown merely
> makes me a little
> reflective.
> 
> Also, bass is something you need to feel, not just
> hear.
> 
> Speaking of getting high off music, read this:
> 
> Ok, here is the absolute key to trancing out to
> trance without using drugs:
> 
> 1. Sit near an air conditioner and have it running a
> little colder then usual
> 2. Turn out the lights
> 3. PLAY THE MUSIC LOUD (I mean as high as you can
> without ear damage)
> preferably with a bass that rumbles your chest.
> 4. Clear your mind of all your current problems in
> life(don't bs me,
> everyone has problems)
> 5. Think about happy stuff, so maybe for you, what
> this track would
> feel like in a crowded club played by your favorite
> DJ while everyone
> is rolling and feeling the same exact vibe as you.
> 6. Throw your arms in the air and yell at the top of
> your lungs
> durring the build up.
> 7. Dance and Feel the fucking music
> 8. If all else fails, listen to harder music
> 
> Most of these can be done in the car, but you better
> not loose your
> concetration on the road. Crashes have happened
> because of trance
> before.
> 
> I wrote that a few years ago for tranceaddict. Yeah,
> well, so I like trance.
> 
> Steve Osteen
> 
> 
>  
>

Ecstatic Dance Ritual

Sep 10, 2005 at the Gatehouse in Fort Mason

Psychic Blast
I woke up one morning and I wish I hadn't.
Conclusions destroyed.
Confusions created.
Convulsions.
You can't prepare for this.
Nothing will save you in this chamber.
Everything you know is worthless.
Nothing here but the raw bite of Death...
The buzzing of silence...
The ecstatic dance of the Void.
The only way to prevent this is by not showing up.

Shamanic Ritual directed by Koyote
Music and Video Projections by Trip Tech

Saturday - Sept 10, 2005 
7:30pm to 11 pm 
At Fort Mason -The Gatehouse
(For directions go to: http://www.fortmason.org/directions/index.html)

Suggested donation: $5.00
For more information on the event go to www.sfbardo.com/talks.htm 

For general information on what is Via Sinistrae, go to: 
http://www.viasinistrae.com/whatis.htm

Pass this email on to anyone you believe might be interested. Thanks!

Juan Carlos
Black Note Music - Techno Shamanic Music
-- Energized Sound Creations --
http://www.deconstructionist.com/blacknote/

"No sage or savior has even endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Osby:

The "facts" that you find on the internet are sometimes stranger than 
truth as fiction.

TO answer your question: "who the fuck is that guy & what the fuck does he 
know?"

Shawn Wallace, from my research online, is staff writer for the
Raves.com website where the article is served:

http://www.raves.com/files/cms/1/Shawn.jpg
Shawn Wallace
Writer
Urbpro@raves.com

I concur the article is definitely written from his point of view.

If you want more info on how he obtained his position @ Raves.com

Here's a public link:

Current Openings: Raves.com is looking for Volunteer Local Reporters to 
review events in their area, and experienced Music Reviewers. Please 
[click here for how to apply] and for details on what is involved.

mailto:jennifer@raves.com?subject=Raves Volunteer Reporter info request

More info on the company:
     Raves.com CEO and Founder Gavin Lloyd

     Site built and designed by: Dmitry Iliev

The question: "What the fuck does he know"

Is debateable.... I personally only take this account as his opinion....

The underground / rave scene here is definitely alive and kicking... 
always has been, it has metamorphosized and evolved...

<3 Karina

On 8/29/05, Karina <karina@hyperreal.org> wrote:
>=20
> Source: http://www.raves.com/features/show/31/THERAVESERA
>=20
>   Written by Shawn Wallace
>=20
> As society changes there are things that will always stand the test of
> time. Each passing generation makes their mark in the best way that they
> know and leave behind the markers of their era. Rave parties are the sort
> an event that brought people together through a common shared interest in
> music and community. The raves were a cultural movement that also defined
> an era in the progression of DJ and club culture.
>=20
> From Outlaw To Main Stage
>=20
> Being involved in the scene has always held a special place for a person.
> Whether it has been scouting out a location for an outlaw party in the
> early days, scribbling out that first handwritten version of the flyer
> that would get the crowds to the site, or trying to find out the best way
> to get power to two turntables in the middle of the woods for hours. In
> the early days, word of mouth was the only way that you could find out
> anything about a rave. You had to know someone who knew someone was who
> was trusted by someone throwing the party to have any chance of knowing
> where to go. Rave parties began as a place where pure enjoyment was drive=
n
> by the music. It wasn't about the outfit you wore or who you knew, it was
> letting the DJ manning the decks take you through an amazing journey
> driven by the ebb and flow of beats and basslines. Standing in lines at
> the parties waiting to drop your five bucks and get your wristband, you
> would notice the diversity of the crowd that was drawn to the events.
> People of all races, genders, sexual orientation, and social standing
> could be found intermixed among the flashing lights and pulsing beats
> moving to one universal groove. As the scene began to grow, dance music
> fans looked for alternative means to get information about the best music=
,
> raves, and clubs. Much of this coming together was accomplished through
> the internet with websites, such as the aptly-titled Raves.com,
> DJ/electronic culture magazines, like BPM, XLR8R, and Mixmag, chat rooms,
> and boards all became an essential piece of the global takeover by raves
> and dance music.
>=20
> The Mainstream Didn't Know What Hit Them
>=20
> As the scene began to expand and more people became involved in the
> process, it was only a matter of time before the mainstream would begin t=
o
> take notice. Suddenly, the rave party was everywhere. It was the place to
> be seen. Kids in day-glo outfits sucking on candy-canes became almost a
> punchline in youth-oriented films coming from Hollywood, the remix became
> the ultimate vehicle for a mainstream artist to gain instant credibility
> with the clubbing elite, and the turntable took over the guitar as the
> must have instrument for the new generation. The biggest sign of the rave
> breakthrough was the birth of the cult of the Superstar DJ, who went from
> being an unknown face in the back of the room just =D1playing records=E2 =
to an
> instant celebrity whose selection of music and tastes could make or beak =
a
> nightclub=C7s future. Finding out where the parties were being held becam=
e
> less of an investigation and more of an artistic venture as the club flye=
r
> took an amazing turn and became an expression of the theme of the
> impending event.
>=20
> The Fall After The Rise
>=20
> In a move that has become typical of any growing youth-based movement, th=
e
> politicians of the day decided to step in and try to use the rave party a=
s
> a tool to garner support for their own grandiose agendas at the expense o=
f
> the clubbers. Never taking into mind the creative DJs, musicians, artists=
,
> promoters, and fans who made up the community surrounding these events.
> This move may have impacted the mainstream exposure of the events, but
> only drove the people behind the scene back into the underground, back to
> where it all began. The move by politicians to focus on the negative side=
s
> of the rave party phenomenon only drove the fans of the culture together
> and created a tighter unit.
>=20
> On the heels of some long, well-fought battles by the clubbing community,
> we made some progress. In the end though, we have seen the rave party
> slowly fade into a distant memory. As superclubs began to focus theme
> nights around DJs and getting numbers in the doors, somewhere along the
> way the party became secondary to creating the next big marketing brand.
> For those of use who were there, raves are a memory that will last
> forever. They were our search for the supernatural and divine place where
> we all come together and one thing is inecapable... we will always have
> the music.
>=20
>=20
> --
> **************************************************************
> ******************>karina@hyperreal.org<**********************
> If there is a sin against life, it consists perhaps not so
> much in despairing of life as in hoping for another life
> & in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.
> -- Albert Camus -- *******************************************
> **************************************************************
>=20
>=20

the set. I just watched a TV show about "all time greatest movie screw ups" 
that documented all sorts of scene and dialogue screw ups, as well costume

definately alive when that flim was shot.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] "Silent" disco? (Tiesto Thread)

Well sometimes you get an army of followers listening to something because 
there is a million dollar marketing machine behind it. Ever think of that? 
Let me give you examples Brittany Spears,Backstreet boys,Nysinch etc.. you 
get it.. Record Execs sit around a room and decide who the next stars are 
going to be it is not neccesarily the artist that has this superior break 
through talent. In tiesto's case I can't say for sure cause im not a fan of 
the music. But I have heard some of his tunes and seen some of his mixing. 
(IMO) it is very simply and that same format of emontial,melodic or cyber 
trance that has been done to DEATH.. nothing special about it. Same build up 
and break downs as all the other tunes. what sets it apart? I would rather 
listen to a nice classical piece of music if I want that same type of 
formula that most trance producers rip off.  Canon in D etc..  With 
marketing machines comes success mixed with a lil talent.

Those are just my 2 bits. Not that Tiesto is a bad DJ he is actually real 
good from a techinical stand point. But his music is very boring to me. I 
can't decipher it from a <Insert local top trance DJ's name here> they all 
sound the same.

Macadio

The New Sesame Street

As written by me, with no regard for the mental health or emotional 
development of your children.

Cookie Monster learns this year that "Cookie is a sometimes food." Next 
year, after struggling with a hundred pound weight gain due to guiltily 
binging on the "sometimes food," Cookie will get his stomach stapled.

It is discovered that Big Bird has been running a series of underground 
bareknuckle boxing clubs with the children of the Street. When arrested, 
he claims it was all the idea of a mysterious figure named Snuffaluffagus. 
Big Bird is institutionalized after screaming "he is me!" and shooting 
himself in the head with an officer's pistol. Miraculously, he survives.

Oscar goes on Prozac. Oscar sleeps all day. Mrs. Oscar, sexually 
unsatisfied, has an affair with the big meathead garbage man who carries 
Oscar around sometimes. Oscar would be dispondent, but he isn't feeling 
much of anything these days.

Mr. Hooper rises from the dead, hungers for the felty brains of muppets. 
Zombie infestation stopped by shotgun wielding Elmo. "Tickle this, zombie 
bitches," says Elmo atop stack of muppet corpse, minus heads.

Bert and Ernie adopt a little boy from Indonesia and dress him like a 
girl. Ten years pass before anyone realizes Angelina is really Angelito.

Count von Count is successfully treated for obsessive compulsive disorder. 
He changes his name back to Herman Goetliber and finally receives his CPA.

Barkley develops a nasty leg-humping habit, has to be put down out back in 
Sesame Alley by a tearful Gordon.
Posted by JeremyT at April 8, 2005 09:00 AM | TrackBack

http://www.cnn.com/2005/US/08/30/ostrich.traffic.ap/index.htmlOstrich breaks free on Golden Gate Bridge
		Tuesday, August 30, 2005; Posted: 1:15 p.m. EDT (17:15 GMT) 
 

SAN FRANCISCO, California (AP) -- Commuters are used to traffic backups during the rush-hour commute on the Golden Gate Bridge. But even this tie-up had to throw some of them for a loop.

An ostrich got loose from a minivan Monday and started roaming around near the toll plaza on the bridge.

Ron Love, the owner of Love Farms, was transporting two of the odd-looking birds in the back of his van. Love was stopped in traffic when he suddenly accelerated, jolting one of the ostriches, who smashed through the back window of the van and got loose on the bridge.

The ostrich began running around on the bridge, stopping traffic for about eight minutes before police were able to move it out of traffic.

"It was quite an adventure," Love said. "Strange things always seem to happen with ostriches. I guess this proves it."

The ostrich had road rash from the fall but was not seriously hurt and was resting comfortably back home, California Highway Patrol Sgt. Wayne Ziese said.

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Love Parade weekend

I may be biased cuz I'm spinning there - but this is really gonna be the 
hotness!

For the Love of Breaks
A Love Parade After-Party
September 24th, 2005
Underground sf location
9pm-6am

Brought to you by Evil Breaks, Subscience, StrategiK, Funky Cactus, 
SFBreaks.org, the Space Cowboys, and everyone with the Bayarea Breaks 
Brigade, this breakbeat underground massive IS where you want to be.


Future Funk Squad (Universal/Default/en:vision) - UK
vs.
High Eight (TCR/Re:connect) - UK

Glen Nicholls (FFS) and Neil Briggs (High Eight) started DJ'ing together 
around 10 years ago, ranging in styles from deep house, big beat, through to 
Drum & Bass. As time went on they both focussed on the "nuskool breaks" 
sound after hearing Tipper's remix of the Grooverider single "Where's Jack 
The Ripper?" and began work on producing tracks. The first single to be 
released was "Shakedown", a much darker, tougher sound that still sounds 
fresh today. Following that the pair released "Pulse" which spawned Glen's 
Default Records label.

Following that, Glen and Neil followed their own production paths with Glen 
continuing the Future Funk Squad name that had already started gaining 
interest, and Neil later with his High Eight project.

The debut Future Funk Squad album, due for release in early 2006, was a 
labour of love for Glen who has brought together talented vocalists and 
songwriters, plus a top notch MC, to produce a varied and surprising mix of 
breaks, hip hop and electronica. Glen has also kept up his dancefloor duties 
by completing remixes for Moloko, Sander Kleinenberg, Mylo and more recently 
The Prodigy.

Neil's High Eight project is still very much in it's infancy, but gaining 
support quickly. His debut single on Re:Connect Recordings was a very 
different sound to his more recent works which have now taken a much more 
80's influenced approach, whilst still maintaining the breaks sound. The 
second single "Open Your Eyes/Thru Time" was a big hit with the many 
differing sides of the breaks fraternity, and his remix work continues 
having scored a major release with TCR records, namely his reworking of 
Rennie Pilgrem's "Gladiator". In 2005 Neil got the opportunity to work with 
one of his favourite 80's icons - Howard Jones - with a remix of his first 
single "New Song".

This year sees the two regroup for some special "versus" gigs, bringing both 
their individual sounds together to form a soundclash of dirty, funky, tough 
breaks. They have also completed some collaborative remixes for Breaks 4 
Ever (Flack.su - Darknesscape) and En:Vision (DJ Phully - Daft Fader), with 
more to come.


Carbon Community (Sober Music/Bless Records) Dallas, TX

J-Break (Afterdark/Painted Puppy) FL

Odeed vs. Wish (Moonshine/W.E.) SoCal

Drag'nfly (Love Tribe/Shaolin/djDragnfly.com) Sacramento


and soooo many more you just wont even be able to take it....



Marc(O)
*THWAP!*//Moksha Tribe//Mario Bros.
DC/MD/VA/CA

Upcoming dates:
9-24-05: LOVE PARADE (Bay 2 Breakin' float and Evil Breaks afterparty)

> For the Love of Breaks

> Brigade, this breakbeat underground massive IS where you want to be.
